WEBVTT

1
00:00:27.778 --> 00:00:29.485
(MOANING SOFTLY)

2
00:00:29.821 --> 00:00:31.607
(MACHINE BEEPING)

3
00:00:37.996 --> 00:00:40.099
<i>NEWSCASTER: ...and I'll tell you what,
the storm system's still moving west.</i>

4
00:00:40.123 --> 00:00:43.115
What are you looking at, Caroline?

5
00:00:44.127 --> 00:00:45.743
CAROLINE: The Wind, Mom.

6
00:00:47.464 --> 00:00:48.704
<i>(YAWNS)</i>

7
00:00:48.799 --> 00:00:51.257
They say the hurricane is coming.

8
00:00:52.886 --> 00:00:56.049
DAISY: I'm on a boat.

9
00:00:56.139 --> 00:00:58.471
I'm drifting.

10
00:01:00.769 --> 00:01:03.056
Can I do anything for you, Mom?

11
00:01:03.146 --> 00:01:04.352
Mmm?

12
00:01:04.439 --> 00:01:06.305
Make anything easier?

13
00:01:07.276 --> 00:01:08.687
Oh, sugar...

14
00:01:09.194 --> 00:01:11.481
There's nothing left to do.

15
00:01:11.989 --> 00:01:13.605
Is what it is.

16
00:01:15.075 --> 00:01:18.067
Finding it harder to keep my eyes open.

17
00:01:19.997 --> 00:01:23.160
My mouth's full of cotton.

18
00:01:23.667 --> 00:01:25.829
DOROTHY: There, there, Miss Daisy.

19
00:01:25.919 --> 00:01:28.661
You gonna scratch yourself to ribbons.

20
00:01:29.506 --> 00:01:31.668
(DAISY SIGHING)

21
00:01:33.552 --> 00:01:36.385
Do you want any more
medication, Mother?

22
00:01:37.264 --> 00:01:40.473
Doctor said you could have
as much as you want.

23
00:01:40.559 --> 00:01:42.846
No need for anybody to suffer.

24
00:01:45.272 --> 00:01:48.890
(THUNDER RUMBLING)

25
00:01:57.826 --> 00:02:00.739
A friend told me
that she never had the chance

26
00:02:00.829 --> 00:02:03.161
to say goodbye to her mother.

27
00:02:06.251 --> 00:02:08.618
- I wanted to...
- It's okay.

28
00:02:08.712 --> 00:02:12.250
I wanted to tell you
how much I'm gonna miss you so...

29
00:02:12.716 --> 00:02:13.831
Mom.

30
00:02:15.802 --> 00:02:17.588
Oh, Caroline.

31
00:02:23.393 --> 00:02:24.883
Are you afraid?

32
00:02:24.978 --> 00:02:26.719
I'm curious.

33
00:02:28.440 --> 00:02:30.101
What comes next?

34
00:02:33.945 --> 00:02:35.527
<i>(TRAIN WHISTLE BLOWING)</i>

35
00:02:35.614 --> 00:02:40.404
They built the train station in 1918.

36
00:02:41.411 --> 00:02:44.199
My father was there the day it opened.

37
00:02:45.832 --> 00:02:48.574
He said they had

38
00:02:50.462 --> 00:02:51.793
a tuba band playing.

39
00:02:52.422 --> 00:02:54.379
(TUBA BAND PLAYING)

40
00:02:56.551 --> 00:03:00.636
They had the finest clockmaker
in all of the South

41
00:03:01.223 --> 00:03:04.056
to build that glorious clock.

42
00:03:05.894 --> 00:03:07.476
<i>His name was...</i>

43
00:03:09.356 --> 00:03:11.188
Mr. Gateau.

44
00:03:12.025 --> 00:03:14.608
<i>(CLOCK CHIMING)</i>

45
00:03:15.529 --> 00:03:16.735
Mr. Cake.

46
00:03:19.282 --> 00:03:23.446
<i>He was married to a Creole
of Evangeline Parish</i>

47
00:03:23.537 --> 00:03:25.778
<i>and they had a son.</i>

48
00:03:27.708 --> 00:03:32.828
<i>Mr. Gateau was, from birth,
absolutely blind.</i>

49
00:03:35.090 --> 00:03:39.334
<i>When their son was old enough,
he joined the army.</i>

50
00:03:40.262 --> 00:03:44.631
<i>And they prayed God would
keep him out of harm's way.</i>

51
00:03:47.561 --> 00:03:52.306
<i>For months,
he did nothing but work on that clock.</i>

52
00:03:56.361 --> 00:03:57.817
<i>One day,</i>

53
00:03:59.156 --> 00:04:01.113
<i>a letter came.</i>

54
00:04:06.329 --> 00:04:10.072
<i>And Mr. Gateau, done for the night,</i>

55
00:04:10.751 --> 00:04:13.288
<i>went up, alone, to bed.</i>

56
00:04:15.922 --> 00:04:18.755
<i>And their son came home.</i>

57
00:04:23.889 --> 00:04:26.722
<i>They buried him in the family plot,</i>

58
00:04:26.808 --> 00:04:30.722
<i>where he would be with them
when their time came.</i>

59
00:04:32.689 --> 00:04:35.852
<i>Mr. Cake worked on his clock,</i>

60
00:04:38.695 --> 00:04:42.313
<i>laboring to finish.</i>

61
00:04:44.201 --> 00:04:47.535
<i>It was a morning to remember.</i>

62
00:04:48.830 --> 00:04:51.993
<i>Papa said
there were people everywhere.</i>

63
00:04:53.376 --> 00:04:55.993
<i>Even Teddy Roosevelt came.</i>

64
00:05:02.052 --> 00:05:04.134
(ALL APPLAUDING)

65
00:05:09.392 --> 00:05:11.633
(CLOCK TICKING)

66
00:05:13.730 --> 00:05:15.596
It's running backwards!

67
00:05:17.234 --> 00:05:18.975
I made it that way

68
00:05:20.570 --> 00:05:22.450
so that perhaps the boys
that we lost in the war

69
00:05:22.531 --> 00:05:23.896
might stand and come home again.

70
00:05:28.787 --> 00:05:30.243
<i>Home to farm,</i>

71
00:05:31.331 --> 00:05:32.571
<i>work,</i>

72
00:05:34.084 --> 00:05:35.825
<i>have children.</i>

73
00:05:39.089 --> 00:05:41.581
<i>To live long, full lives.</i>

74
00:05:44.761 --> 00:05:47.469
Perhaps my own son
might come home again.

75
00:05:56.106 --> 00:05:58.689
I'm sorry if I've offended anybody.

76
00:06:00.235 --> 00:06:02.522
I hope you enjoy my clock.

77
00:06:03.405 --> 00:06:07.273
<i>DAISY: Mr. Cake was never seen again.</i>

78
00:06:11.621 --> 00:06:16.081
<i>Some say he died of a broken heart.</i>

79
00:06:17.794 --> 00:06:20.126
<i>Some say he went to sea.</i>

80
00:06:25.218 --> 00:06:26.379
DOROTHY: Excuse me.

81
00:06:26.469 --> 00:06:29.052
Do you mind if I make a call?
Somebody's watching my little boy.

82
00:06:29.139 --> 00:06:30.425
Sure.

83
00:06:40.650 --> 00:06:42.891
I hope I haven't disappointed you.

84
00:06:42.986 --> 00:06:46.104
You couldn't disappoint me.

85
00:06:47.532 --> 00:06:52.447
Well, I know I don't have much
to show for myself.

86
00:06:54.998 --> 00:06:57.456
Find my dark suitcase.

87
00:07:01.796 --> 00:07:04.709
There's a diary.

88
00:07:06.843 --> 00:07:07.958
This?

89
00:07:10.680 --> 00:07:13.593
Could you read it to me?

90
00:07:14.059 --> 00:07:16.391
Is this what you want to do?

91
00:07:16.478 --> 00:07:20.392
I tried to read it
a hundred different times.

92
00:07:21.358 --> 00:07:23.349
Mom, it's not exactly...

93
00:07:23.443 --> 00:07:26.856
It's just the sound
of your voice, darling.

94
00:07:27.489 --> 00:07:28.695
Okay.

95
00:07:29.824 --> 00:07:30.859
Oh.

96
00:07:31.826 --> 00:07:34.818
It's dated April 4th, 1985.

97
00:07:35.914 --> 00:07:38.281
And it says New Orleans.

98
00:07:38.375 --> 00:07:41.117
"This is my last will and testament.

99
00:07:41.211 --> 00:07:45.421
"I don't have much to leave,
few possessions, no money, really.

100
00:07:45.799 --> 00:07:51.044
"I will go out of this world the same way
I came in, alone and with nothing.

101
00:07:51.721 --> 00:07:53.587
"All I have is my story,

102
00:07:53.682 --> 00:07:57.095
"and I'm writing it now
while I still remember it.

103
00:07:57.894 --> 00:08:01.057
"My name is Benjamin.
Benjamin Button."

104
00:08:01.398 --> 00:08:04.561
<i>BENJAMIN: And I was born under
unusual circumstances.</i>

105
00:08:05.485 --> 00:08:07.726
<i>The First World War had ended,</i>

106
00:08:08.405 --> 00:08:12.319
<i>and We been told it was
an especially good night to be born.</i>

107
00:08:12.409 --> 00:08:13.820
(BAND PLAYING)

108
00:08:13.910 --> 00:08:16.117
MAN 1: Thank God it's over!

109
00:08:16.204 --> 00:08:18.036
MAN 2: We won the war!

110
00:08:18.123 --> 00:08:20.160
(PEOPLE CHEERING)

111
00:08:25.255 --> 00:08:27.292
(CAR HORN HONKING)

112
00:08:32.929 --> 00:08:34.761
MAN 3: The Great War is over!

113
00:08:46.985 --> 00:08:48.020
What are you doing here?

114
00:08:48.111 --> 00:08:49.442
Thomas,

115
00:08:50.655 --> 00:08:52.111
I'm afraid she's going to die.

116
00:08:52.198 --> 00:08:53.404
What?

117
00:08:54.534 --> 00:08:58.198
That's enough.
All of you, get away from her.

118
00:08:58.288 --> 00:09:00.325
(CRYING)

119
00:09:01.374 --> 00:09:04.492
I came as quickly as I could.
The streets are filled with people.

120
00:09:04.586 --> 00:09:05.872
Thomas.

121
00:09:06.337 --> 00:09:08.954
Promise me he has a place.

122
00:09:11.342 --> 00:09:12.503
Yeah.

123
00:09:13.845 --> 00:09:15.882
<i>BENJAMIN: She gave her life for me.</i>

124
00:09:16.890 --> 00:09:19.882
<i>And for that, I am forever grateful.</i>

125
00:09:20.143 --> 00:09:21.884
(BENJAMIN CRYING)

126
00:09:29.486 --> 00:09:30.897
Mr. Button.

127
00:09:37.786 --> 00:09:39.197
(GASPS)

128
00:09:41.498 --> 00:09:42.784
(CHANTING)

129
00:09:44.626 --> 00:09:46.082
(GRUNTING)

130
00:09:46.169 --> 00:09:47.409
Thomas!

131
00:09:47.504 --> 00:09:48.790
Thomas.

132
00:09:48.963 --> 00:09:50.328
(BENJAMIN CONTINUES CRYING)

133
00:09:50.757 --> 00:09:52.964
Thomas? Where are you going?

134
00:09:59.933 --> 00:10:01.844
(BENJAMIN SCREAMING)

135
00:10:21.538 --> 00:10:23.905
POLICEMAN: Hey!
What are you doing there?

136
00:10:25.125 --> 00:10:27.207
What do you have there?

137
00:10:29.045 --> 00:10:30.410
(WHISTLE BLOWING)

138
00:10:59.409 --> 00:11:01.616
(PANTING)

139
00:11:23.558 --> 00:11:24.719
(SHUSHING)

140
00:11:24.809 --> 00:11:27.176
TIZZY: Come on, Queenie.
QUEENIE: Now, Mr. Weathers!

141
00:11:27.270 --> 00:11:30.638
Come on, now, you know I ain't got
nothing but work to do around here.

142
00:11:30.732 --> 00:11:33.092
- Come on. Just take some time.
- Stop all this foolishness.

143
00:11:36.196 --> 00:11:37.982
The air is sweet.

144
00:11:38.281 --> 00:11:39.692
(FIRECRACKERS BURSTING)

145
00:11:42.410 --> 00:11:45.493
You look very handsome tonight,
Miss Queenie.

146
00:11:46.789 --> 00:11:48.951
Handsome as I've ever seen.

147
00:11:50.376 --> 00:11:52.617
The brown matches your eyes.

148
00:11:52.712 --> 00:11:54.043
Oh, hush!

149
00:11:54.130 --> 00:11:55.416
(BOTH LAUGHING)

150
00:11:55.506 --> 00:11:59.670
Let's see here.
You ain't no slouch yourself.

151
00:12:08.228 --> 00:12:10.060
TIZZY: Hambert's back in town.

152
00:12:10.146 --> 00:12:13.935
He came home legless, but he's home.

153
00:12:14.901 --> 00:12:17.563
I know you were
sweet on him one time.

154
00:12:18.071 --> 00:12:19.937
Sweeter than I should've been.

155
00:12:20.031 --> 00:12:21.942
Miss Simone messed herself.

156
00:12:22.033 --> 00:12:23.273
Oh, sweet Jesus.

157
00:12:23.368 --> 00:12:25.905
She got to stop doing that
or it's diapers for her.

158
00:12:25.995 --> 00:12:28.140
- I'll be right there, Miss Jameson!
- Now, Queenie, now come on.

159
00:12:28.164 --> 00:12:30.747
MRS. JAMESON:
Okay, Queenie'll be right there.

160
00:12:30.833 --> 00:12:32.073
It's awful nice out here.

161
00:12:32.168 --> 00:12:35.411
Come on out back for a moment.
Take your mind off things.

162
00:12:35.505 --> 00:12:36.540
QUEENIE: You're so bad.

163
00:12:36.631 --> 00:12:39.089
- What in God's name?
- What's this?

164
00:12:39.175 --> 00:12:40.916
(BENJAMIN SCREAMING)

165
00:12:42.762 --> 00:12:44.218
(GASPING)

166
00:12:49.477 --> 00:12:51.718
QUEENIE: Oh, the Lord
done something here.

167
00:12:51.813 --> 00:12:55.306
Hope I didn't hurt it none
stepping on it like that.

168
00:12:55.400 --> 00:12:56.936
We best leave that for the police.

169
00:12:57.026 --> 00:12:58.562
Poor baby.

170
00:12:59.362 --> 00:13:00.727
I'll go.

171
00:13:01.364 --> 00:13:05.073
It's for sure nobody wanted to keep it.
Come on, baby.

172
00:13:06.619 --> 00:13:07.619
(PIANO PLAYING)

173
00:13:07.704 --> 00:13:10.162
MRS. JAMESON: Queenie?
Where are you, Queenie?

174
00:13:10.248 --> 00:13:12.205
Hold your water! You go deal with it.

175
00:13:12.292 --> 00:13:14.408
Okay. No, go, I'll be back.

176
00:13:15.253 --> 00:13:18.541
WOMAN: Queenie, Apple, she went
and messed herself all over again!

177
00:13:18.631 --> 00:13:20.497
Jane Childress, start her a bath!

178
00:13:20.591 --> 00:13:22.673
And mind your own business,
Mrs. Duprey.

179
00:13:22.760 --> 00:13:24.592
You'll be messing yourself
soon enough.

180
00:13:24.679 --> 00:13:26.261
Somebody stole my necklace.

181
00:13:26.347 --> 00:13:29.305
Okay. All right, Mrs. Hollister,
I'll be right with you, okay?

182
00:13:29.392 --> 00:13:31.599
Go on back upstairs, hear?

183
00:13:32.687 --> 00:13:34.098
(BENJAMIN CRYING)

184
00:13:37.900 --> 00:13:40.437
You are as ugly as an old pot

185
00:13:40.528 --> 00:13:42.189
but you're still a child of God.

186
00:13:42.280 --> 00:13:44.647
WOMAN: Queenie, Apple,
she won't take a bath without you!

187
00:13:44.741 --> 00:13:46.231
Mercy.

188
00:13:46.326 --> 00:13:48.317
I'll be right there!

189
00:13:51.331 --> 00:13:54.289
Okay. You just wait right here
for me now, okay?

190
00:13:56.502 --> 00:13:57.502
(BOTH GASP)

191
00:13:57.587 --> 00:14:02.252
My sister gave me those pearls.
I can't find them anywhere.

192
00:14:02.342 --> 00:14:06.176
- Somebody's been stealing my jewelry.
- They're right here, Mrs. Hollister. See?

193
00:14:06.262 --> 00:14:09.596
Right around your pretty white neck.
Now, come on. Hush all that noise.

194
00:14:09.682 --> 00:14:12.299
- Is Dr. Rose still here?
- I don't know.

195
00:14:15.104 --> 00:14:16.390
Your heart is strong.

196
00:14:16.481 --> 00:14:19.473
You just want to avoid
any undue stimulation.

197
00:14:20.068 --> 00:14:23.186
I trust you ladies will
help me out with that?

198
00:14:23.279 --> 00:14:26.442
I have something.
Could you come downstairs?

199
00:14:30.119 --> 00:14:33.828
Never seen anything like it.
Nearly blind from cataracts.

200
00:14:33.915 --> 00:14:38.000
I'm not sure if he can hear.
His bones indicate severe arthritis.

201
00:14:38.795 --> 00:14:43.210
His skin has lost all elasticity,
and his hands and feet are ossified.

202
00:14:43.299 --> 00:14:47.884
He shows all the deterioration,
the infirmities, not of a newborn,

203
00:14:47.970 --> 00:14:50.632
but of a man well in his 80s
on his way to the grave.

204
00:14:50.723 --> 00:14:51.723
He's dying?

205
00:14:51.808 --> 00:14:54.391
His body is failing him
before his life's begun.

206
00:14:54.477 --> 00:14:55.888
(GROANING)

207
00:14:57.438 --> 00:14:58.894
Where'd he come from?

208
00:14:58.981 --> 00:15:03.350
My sister's child. From Lafayette.
She had an unfortunate adventure.

209
00:15:03.444 --> 00:15:07.358
The poor child, he got the worst of it.
Come out white.

210
00:15:10.368 --> 00:15:14.987
There are places for unwanted babies
like these, Queenie.

211
00:15:15.623 --> 00:15:18.285
No room for another mouth to feed here.

212
00:15:18.376 --> 00:15:20.913
The Nolan Foundation,
despite their good intentions,

213
00:15:21.003 --> 00:15:23.791
thinks this place is
a large nuisance as it is.

214
00:15:23.881 --> 00:15:26.088
- A baby...
- You said he don't have long.

215
00:15:26.175 --> 00:15:30.760
Queenie, some creatures
aren't meant to survive.

216
00:15:34.142 --> 00:15:37.885
No, this baby, he is a miracle.
That's for certain.

217
00:15:37.979 --> 00:15:41.017
Just not the kind of miracle
one hopes to see.

218
00:15:44.026 --> 00:15:46.518
Y'all listen. Y'all listen up here.

219
00:15:47.280 --> 00:15:48.382
We're gonna have us a visitor

220
00:15:48.406 --> 00:15:51.524
that's gonna be staying
with us for a little while.

221
00:15:51.617 --> 00:15:55.360
My sister had a child and
she couldn't see right by it, so...

222
00:15:57.582 --> 00:15:59.368
He's known as...

223
00:16:02.587 --> 00:16:03.918
Benjamin.

224
00:16:04.547 --> 00:16:05.878
Benjamin.

225
00:16:06.757 --> 00:16:09.715
He's not a well child, so we're gonna
have to take good care of him.

226
00:16:09.802 --> 00:16:10.883
I had 10 children.

227
00:16:10.970 --> 00:16:14.338
There's not a baby I can't care for.
Let me see him.

228
00:16:16.517 --> 00:16:19.805
God in Heaven.
He looks just like my ex-husband.

229
00:16:19.896 --> 00:16:20.896
(ALL LAUGHING)

230
00:16:20.980 --> 00:16:23.642
Look, he's prematurely old.

231
00:16:24.108 --> 00:16:27.692
Dr. Rose said he ain't got
much more time on this earth.

232
00:16:27.987 --> 00:16:29.148
MAN: Join the club.

233
00:16:29.238 --> 00:16:30.774
(ALL CHUCKLING)

234
00:16:34.243 --> 00:16:35.733
WOMAN: He's smiling!

235
00:16:42.460 --> 00:16:45.168
Hambert sends his
remembrances to you.

236
00:16:45.254 --> 00:16:46.870
(BENJAMIN GURGLING)

237
00:16:54.931 --> 00:16:57.298
Are you right out of your mind?

238
00:16:58.601 --> 00:17:01.969
I know you ain't got all the parts
it takes to make one of your own,

239
00:17:02.063 --> 00:17:03.303
but this ain't yours to keep.

240
00:17:03.397 --> 00:17:05.684
It may not even be human kind.

241
00:17:14.784 --> 00:17:17.242
Mr. Weathers, come back here.

242
00:17:19.539 --> 00:17:20.779
Please.

243
00:17:25.127 --> 00:17:26.127
(SIGHS)

244
00:17:37.139 --> 00:17:39.722
You never know
what's coming for you.

245
00:17:49.694 --> 00:17:52.106
<i>BENJAMIN: It seemed
I had found a home.</i>

246
00:17:55.241 --> 00:17:56.322
Is any of this true?

247
00:17:56.409 --> 00:17:59.822
You have such a lovely voice.

248
00:18:00.329 --> 00:18:05.039
Morn, it's an ancient streetcar token.

249
00:18:06.711 --> 00:18:09.874
That clock just kept going,

250
00:18:10.840 --> 00:18:15.084
year after year after year.

251
00:18:19.348 --> 00:18:21.259
<i>BENJAMIN: But I didn't
know I was a child.</i>

252
00:18:21.350 --> 00:18:23.842
Same old crap every day.

253
00:18:24.729 --> 00:18:27.187
<i>I thought I was like
everyone else there.</i>

254
00:18:27.273 --> 00:18:28.434
(FORK CLANGING)

255
00:18:28.524 --> 00:18:30.686
<i>An old man in the twilight of his life.</i>

256
00:18:30.776 --> 00:18:33.143
WOMAN: Could you make him stop that?

257
00:18:34.113 --> 00:18:37.196
Stop banging that fork.
It's used for eating, not for playing with.

258
00:18:37.283 --> 00:18:40.150
And use your napkin,
please, Mr. Benjamin.

259
00:18:42.496 --> 00:18:43.782
WOMAN: Queenie!

260
00:18:55.843 --> 00:18:57.174
Hey, boy.

261
00:18:59.388 --> 00:19:01.720
(CHILDREN LAUGHING)

262
00:19:04.518 --> 00:19:06.850
<i>BENJAMIN: Always
had a healthy curiosity.</i>

263
00:19:07.980 --> 00:19:11.473
<i>What was up the street?
Or around the next corner?</i>

264
00:19:13.319 --> 00:19:14.650
BOY: Go get him!

265
00:19:14.737 --> 00:19:18.446
Benjamin! That is dangerous.
Come back over here.

266
00:19:19.158 --> 00:19:20.899
Stay put, child.

267
00:19:23.245 --> 00:19:25.236
<i>BENJAMIN: I loved her very much.</i>

268
00:19:25.998 --> 00:19:27.659
<i>She was my mother.</i>

269
00:19:27.750 --> 00:19:28.911
Mama.

270
00:19:29.585 --> 00:19:30.746
Mama.

271
00:19:31.545 --> 00:19:35.334
Some days I feel different
than the day before.

272
00:19:36.759 --> 00:19:40.798
Everybody feels different about
themselves, one way or another.

273
00:19:41.764 --> 00:19:44.096
But we're all going the same way.

274
00:19:45.434 --> 00:19:49.098
Just taking different roads
to get there, that's all.

275
00:19:49.188 --> 00:19:51.680
You're on your own road, Benjamin.

276
00:19:54.443 --> 00:19:57.105
Mama? How much longer I got?

277
00:19:57.613 --> 00:20:00.901
Just be thankful for
what you're given, hear?

278
00:20:00.991 --> 00:20:04.109
You're already here longer
than you're supposed to.

279
00:20:06.956 --> 00:20:09.914
<i>BENJAMIN: Some nights,
I'd have to sleep alone.</i>

280
00:20:18.592 --> 00:20:20.299
<i>I didn't mind.</i>

281
00:20:21.137 --> 00:20:23.925
<i>I would listen to the house breathing.</i>

282
00:20:25.099 --> 00:20:27.181
<i>All those people sleeping.</i>

283
00:20:28.644 --> 00:20:30.851
<i>I felt safe.</i>

284
00:20:50.458 --> 00:20:51.573
(CRASHING)

285
00:20:51.667 --> 00:20:54.284
<i>It was a place of great routine.</i>

286
00:20:54.378 --> 00:20:57.291
<i>Every morning at 5:30,
no matter the weather,</i>

287
00:20:57.381 --> 00:21:01.500
<i>General Winslow, U. S. Army, Retired,
would raise the flag.</i>

288
00:21:04.346 --> 00:21:08.305
<i>Mrs. Sybil Wagner,
once an opera singer of some note,</i>

289
00:21:08.392 --> 00:21:11.054
<i>well, she sang Wagner.</i>

290
00:21:11.312 --> 00:21:14.725
(SINGING)

291
00:21:22.865 --> 00:21:24.276
QUEENIE: All right, baby, come on.

292
00:21:24.366 --> 00:21:28.234
We got to put some life
into these old sticks for you.

293
00:21:28.329 --> 00:21:32.664
Get you walking so you can help me out
around here. Come on now, hear?

294
00:21:33.709 --> 00:21:37.577
<i>BENJAMIN: No matter the season,
supper was served promptly at 5:30.</i>

295
00:21:37.671 --> 00:21:39.833
BENJAMIN: Molasses.

296
00:21:39.924 --> 00:21:41.210
Molasses.

297
00:21:42.384 --> 00:21:44.000
Molasses.

298
00:21:44.929 --> 00:21:47.512
I learned to read when I was five.

299
00:21:48.557 --> 00:21:51.970
My grandfather was a
dresser for a famous actor.

300
00:21:52.061 --> 00:21:54.803
He brung home every
play for me to read.

301
00:21:57.024 --> 00:22:00.767
"Kind keepers of my weak decaying age,

302
00:22:01.695 --> 00:22:05.313
"Let dying Mortimer here rest himself.

303
00:22:06.075 --> 00:22:08.817
"Even like a man new
haled from the rack,

304
00:22:08.911 --> 00:22:11.619
"So fare my limbs
with long imprisonment.

305
00:22:12.331 --> 00:22:15.995
"And these gray locks,
the pursuivants of death,

306
00:22:16.585 --> 00:22:19.577
"Argue the end of Edmund Mortimer."

307
00:22:21.841 --> 00:22:23.377
(CHUCKLES)

308
00:22:23.467 --> 00:22:26.550
You thought I was plain
ignorant, didn't you?

309
00:22:26.637 --> 00:22:30.301
The actor my grandfather worked
for was John Wilkes Booth.

310
00:22:32.601 --> 00:22:34.638
He killed Abraham Lincoln.

311
00:22:36.397 --> 00:22:39.059
You never know
what's coming for you.

312
00:22:39.733 --> 00:22:43.351
<i>BENJAMIN: On Saturday nights,
Mama would make me go to church.</i>

313
00:22:47.116 --> 00:22:48.527
Benjamin!

314
00:22:48.617 --> 00:22:50.324
(ALL SINGING)

315
00:22:58.836 --> 00:23:01.043
- Amen! Amen!
- Amen! Amen!

316
00:23:03.007 --> 00:23:05.374
What can I do for you, sister?

317
00:23:08.095 --> 00:23:09.095
(WHISPERING)

318
00:23:15.185 --> 00:23:19.975
Her parts are all twisted up inside
and she can't have little children.

319
00:23:20.190 --> 00:23:21.396
(ALL EXCLAIMING)

320
00:23:24.486 --> 00:23:28.525
Lord, if you could see clear
to forgive this woman her sins

321
00:23:28.616 --> 00:23:30.732
so she can bear
the fruit of the womb.

322
00:23:30.826 --> 00:23:33.238
Out, damnable affliction!

323
00:23:33.329 --> 00:23:35.491
- Praise God!
- Praise God!

324
00:23:35.581 --> 00:23:36.742
Hallelujah!

325
00:23:36.832 --> 00:23:38.322
- Hallelujah!
- Hallelujah!

326
00:23:40.377 --> 00:23:43.165
And what's this old man's irrediction?

327
00:23:44.840 --> 00:23:46.251
He's got the Devil on his back,

328
00:23:46.342 --> 00:23:49.676
trying to ride him into
the grave before his time.

329
00:23:52.932 --> 00:23:54.388
- Out, Zebuchar!
- Yes!

330
00:23:54.475 --> 00:23:56.341
- Out, Beelzebub!
- Yes!

331
00:23:58.187 --> 00:23:59.928
How old are you?

332
00:24:00.022 --> 00:24:02.559
Seven. But I look a lot older.

333
00:24:03.609 --> 00:24:05.145
God bless you.

334
00:24:05.694 --> 00:24:07.184
He's seven.

335
00:24:07.279 --> 00:24:08.519
(ALL LAUGHING)

336
00:24:09.990 --> 00:24:13.949
Now, this is a man with
optimism in his heart.

337
00:24:14.036 --> 00:24:15.743
- All right.
- Belief in his soul!

338
00:24:15.829 --> 00:24:16.829
- Yes!
- Yes!

339
00:24:16.914 --> 00:24:18.746
We are all children in the eyes of God!

340
00:24:18.832 --> 00:24:20.118
- Yes!
- Hallelujah!

341
00:24:20.209 --> 00:24:23.122
We are gonna get you out of that chair.

342
00:24:23.212 --> 00:24:25.249
- And we're gonna have you walk.
- WOMAN: Amen.

343
00:24:26.090 --> 00:24:27.706
It's all right.

344
00:24:28.592 --> 00:24:30.833
In the name of God's glory...

345
00:24:31.679 --> 00:24:33.135
Rise up!

346
00:24:34.598 --> 00:24:36.009
QUEENIE: Come on.

347
00:24:37.810 --> 00:24:39.596
MAN 1: Come on. Walk.

348
00:24:39.687 --> 00:24:41.143
Come on, son. Come on.

349
00:24:41.230 --> 00:24:43.972
- Come on with it, son. Come on.
- MAN 2: Come on.

350
00:24:44.066 --> 00:24:47.434
Now God is gonna see
you the rest of the way.

351
00:24:47.528 --> 00:24:52.318
He's gonna see this little old man walk
without the use of a crutch or a cane.

352
00:24:52.408 --> 00:24:54.240
He's gonna see that
you walk from faith...

353
00:24:54.326 --> 00:24:57.318
- Hallelujah!
- ...and divine inspiration alone!

354
00:24:57.413 --> 00:24:58.574
- Yes.
- Hey, Ben!

355
00:24:58.664 --> 00:24:59.995
- WOMAN: Go, son!
- Now walk.

356
00:25:00.082 --> 00:25:01.322
- Yes.
- Come on.

357
00:25:02.334 --> 00:25:03.334
(ALL GASPING)

358
00:25:03.419 --> 00:25:05.080
Don't touch him.

359
00:25:07.423 --> 00:25:09.209
Rise up, old man.

360
00:25:10.259 --> 00:25:12.842
Rise up like Lazarus.

361
00:25:12.928 --> 00:25:15.090
I said, rise up!

362
00:25:15.723 --> 00:25:17.088
MAN 3: Hallelujah!

363
00:25:19.268 --> 00:25:20.474
Yes.

364
00:25:20.936 --> 00:25:22.142
Come on.

365
00:25:22.229 --> 00:25:23.229
Say hallelujah.

366
00:25:23.313 --> 00:25:24.724
- Hallelujah!
- Hallelujah!

367
00:25:26.442 --> 00:25:27.648
Walk.

368
00:25:28.444 --> 00:25:30.526
Walk on. Yes.

369
00:25:34.366 --> 00:25:35.401
That's right, Benjamin.

370
00:25:35.492 --> 00:25:38.735
<i>BENJAMIN: Now when I look back on it,
it was miraculous.</i>

371
00:25:38.829 --> 00:25:42.914
<i>But you know the saying, the Lord
giveth and the Lord taketh away.</i>

372
00:25:43.125 --> 00:25:45.036
Glory in the highest!

373
00:25:47.880 --> 00:25:48.961
(PEOPLE EXCLAIMING)

374
00:25:49.131 --> 00:25:50.292
Sweet Jesus!

375
00:25:50.424 --> 00:25:51.539
- No!
- No!

376
00:25:51.633 --> 00:25:52.873
(WOMEN SCREAMING)

377
00:25:53.969 --> 00:25:55.405
<i>BENJAMIN: There were
so many birthdays.</i>

378
00:25:55.429 --> 00:25:58.967
(SINGING) <i>For he's a jolly good fellow
For he's a jolly good fellow...</i>

379
00:25:59.058 --> 00:26:01.675
<i>BENJAMIN: So we wouldn't run out,
we would spare the candles.</i>

380
00:26:01.769 --> 00:26:05.808
Queenie, you know I don't like
birthdays and I don't like cake.

381
00:26:06.482 --> 00:26:10.476
<i>And death was a common visitor.
People came and went.</i>

382
00:26:12.279 --> 00:26:14.691
<i>You always knew
when someone left us.</i>

383
00:26:14.782 --> 00:26:17.319
<i>There was a silence in the house.</i>

384
00:26:19.328 --> 00:26:21.490
<i>(GRAMAPHONE PLAYING WAGNER)</i>

385
00:26:31.340 --> 00:26:33.627
<i>It was a wonderful place to grow up.</i>

386
00:26:33.717 --> 00:26:38.211
<i>I was with people who had shed
all the inconsequences of earlier life.</i>

387
00:26:38.889 --> 00:26:43.008
<i>Left wondering about the weather,
the temperature of a bath,</i>

388
00:26:44.228 --> 00:26:46.469
<i>the light at the end of a day.</i>

389
00:26:46.730 --> 00:26:47.730
(MAN FARTS)

390
00:26:50.859 --> 00:26:54.853
<i>For everyone that died, someone
would come to take their place.</i>

391
00:26:55.864 --> 00:26:58.196
OTI: I've been married five times.

392
00:26:58.700 --> 00:27:02.409
My fifth wife and I are captured
by a neighbor tribe of cannibals.

393
00:27:02.496 --> 00:27:03.640
WOMAN 1: Oh, goodness gracious.

394
00:27:03.664 --> 00:27:05.120
OTI: We escaped across the river.

395
00:27:05.207 --> 00:27:08.620
My wife, she can't swim,
so, sadly, she eaten.

396
00:27:08.710 --> 00:27:09.916
WOMAN 2: Oh, my God.

397
00:27:10.003 --> 00:27:12.870
OTI: My second wife
steps on cobra and dies.

398
00:27:13.382 --> 00:27:16.170
It was very bad luck
to be married to me.

399
00:27:16.260 --> 00:27:19.298
That's Mr. Oti. He's an acquaintance
of an acquaintance of mine.

400
00:27:19.388 --> 00:27:21.508
- OTI: The next summer I'm captured...
- He's a Pygmy.

401
00:27:21.598 --> 00:27:23.464
...with three others
by the Baschiele tribe.

402
00:27:23.559 --> 00:27:28.474
They trade us for pigs, shoes, and beer
to a very strange American man.

403
00:27:28.564 --> 00:27:30.100
(ALL EXCLAIMING)

404
00:27:47.583 --> 00:27:50.075
I hear you're not so
old as you're looking.

405
00:27:50.169 --> 00:27:52.410
You just fooling everybody.

406
00:27:52.963 --> 00:27:56.001
What's the matter?
Did you get <i>Madjembe?</i>

407
00:27:56.091 --> 00:27:57.502
What's <i>Madjembe</i>?

408
00:27:57.593 --> 00:27:58.924
Worms.

409
00:27:59.261 --> 00:28:01.593
I don't think I have worms.

410
00:28:02.222 --> 00:28:03.758
This is just how I am.

411
00:28:03.849 --> 00:28:06.716
QUEENIE: Did you take your pills today?
MAN: No, ma'am.

412
00:28:06.810 --> 00:28:09.177
Come. Let's get a cold root beer.

413
00:28:09.271 --> 00:28:11.387
I found the medication
under your pillow.

414
00:28:11.481 --> 00:28:14.690
I'm not supposed to. It's dangerous.

415
00:28:14.776 --> 00:28:17.518
Who said that? Come on, little man.

416
00:28:18.780 --> 00:28:20.487
Hello, children.

417
00:28:31.710 --> 00:28:33.075
Hold, please.

418
00:28:33.170 --> 00:28:34.170
(TRAM BELL RINGS)

419
00:28:35.881 --> 00:28:40.216
Then I'm in the monkey house
at Philadelphia Zoological Park.

420
00:28:41.094 --> 00:28:44.632
Three thousand people
show up my first day.

421
00:28:45.933 --> 00:28:46.968
Look.

422
00:28:48.727 --> 00:28:50.638
BENJAMIN: What's it
like living in a cage?

423
00:28:50.729 --> 00:28:52.219
It stinks.

424
00:28:52.814 --> 00:28:55.146
But the monkeys.

425
00:28:55.901 --> 00:28:57.983
They do some tricks there.

426
00:28:58.153 --> 00:29:00.895
I throw a spear, wrestle with Kowali.

427
00:29:01.698 --> 00:29:03.484
She is orangutan.

428
00:29:03.867 --> 00:29:07.405
When I'm not playing with the monkeys,
they want me to run to the bars

429
00:29:07.496 --> 00:29:09.658
in my cage, with my teeth.

430
00:29:11.333 --> 00:29:12.664
(GROWLING)

431
00:29:12.751 --> 00:29:14.116
(SCREAMING)

432
00:29:14.878 --> 00:29:16.494
(BOTH LAUGHING)

433
00:29:19.549 --> 00:29:21.631
BENJAMIN: So then what'd you do?

434
00:29:21.718 --> 00:29:27.589
Then I leave 200, go here, go there.
Wandered most of the time.

435
00:29:28.016 --> 00:29:29.097
You were all alone?

436
00:29:29.184 --> 00:29:31.471
Plenty of time you'll be alone.

437
00:29:31.561 --> 00:29:35.020
When you're different like us,
it's gonna be that way.

438
00:29:38.026 --> 00:29:39.892
But I'll tell you a little secret.

439
00:29:39.987 --> 00:29:43.275
Fat people, skinny people, tall people,

440
00:29:43.365 --> 00:29:46.403
white people,
they're just as alone as we are.

441
00:29:46.910 --> 00:29:49.151
But they're scared shitless.

442
00:29:55.335 --> 00:29:57.997
I think about the river I grew up on.

443
00:29:58.422 --> 00:30:01.380
It would be nice to
sit by my river again.

444
00:30:03.593 --> 00:30:06.005
Come, I have an appointment.

445
00:30:08.390 --> 00:30:10.973
There's my little man.
You ready, sugar?

446
00:30:11.059 --> 00:30:13.391
Always ready. Always ready.

447
00:30:15.188 --> 00:30:17.304
Filamena, Mr. Benjamin.

448
00:30:18.317 --> 00:30:21.400
- It's a pleasure to meet you, sir.
- My pleasure, ma'am.

449
00:30:21.486 --> 00:30:23.477
You can find your own
way home, can't you?

450
00:30:23.572 --> 00:30:26.314
Take the St. Charles line to Napoleon.

451
00:30:32.289 --> 00:30:33.905
Hey! Hey!

452
00:30:54.227 --> 00:30:57.765
Where in God's name have you been?
Get in here.

453
00:30:59.232 --> 00:31:02.520
I mean, you take my breath away,
you know that?

454
00:31:02.903 --> 00:31:05.520
Oh, Lord, I was so worried about you.

455
00:31:09.201 --> 00:31:11.784
<i>BENJAMIN: It had been
the best day of my life.</i>

456
00:31:12.704 --> 00:31:15.412
- How's her breathing?
- It's shallow.

457
00:31:15.499 --> 00:31:17.059
They say it'll reach us in a few hours,

458
00:31:17.125 --> 00:31:20.038
so I gotta get my baby
and take him to my sister's.

459
00:31:20.128 --> 00:31:22.620
They say there's nothing to
worry about here in the hospital.

460
00:31:22.714 --> 00:31:25.206
Nurses'll be right here if you need them.
Are you okay?

461
00:31:25.300 --> 00:31:29.089
- Yeah, I'm okay reading.
- I shouldn't be more than an hour.

462
00:31:30.472 --> 00:31:33.134
Was there just company?

463
00:31:33.642 --> 00:31:36.100
It was just Dorothy leaving.

464
00:31:38.230 --> 00:31:39.686
Go on, Caroline.

465
00:31:39.773 --> 00:31:42.891
"On Sundays, the families
would come and visit."

466
00:31:43.276 --> 00:31:46.234
<i>BENJAMIN: It was Thanksgiving, 1930.</i>

467
00:31:46.321 --> 00:31:49.313
<i>I met the person
who changed my life forever.</i>

468
00:31:51.201 --> 00:31:52.817
(CAR HORN HONKING)

469
00:32:01.336 --> 00:32:03.452
Well, Benjamin.

470
00:32:03.839 --> 00:32:07.173
Might I say you are
looking strikingly youthful.

471
00:32:07.634 --> 00:32:09.216
Good day, Mrs. Fuller.

472
00:32:09.302 --> 00:32:12.590
A single cane,
back straight as an arrow.

473
00:32:12.681 --> 00:32:15.048
What elixir have you been drinking?

474
00:32:15.142 --> 00:32:18.510
- Thank you, ma'am.
- Grandma! Look at me!

475
00:32:20.939 --> 00:32:23.271
That was really something.

476
00:32:23.358 --> 00:32:25.269
Come on over here, you.

477
00:32:25.360 --> 00:32:28.193
Now, this is my granddaughter, Daisy.

478
00:32:29.114 --> 00:32:30.980
This is Mr...

479
00:32:31.074 --> 00:32:34.783
I'm afraid, Benjamin,
I don't rightly know your last name.

480
00:32:34.870 --> 00:32:36.531
Benjamin's fine.

481
00:32:37.122 --> 00:32:39.489
<i>BENJAMIN: I never
forgot her blue eyes.</i>

482
00:32:39.875 --> 00:32:42.583
Good people, supper is served.

483
00:32:42.669 --> 00:32:48.790
Health and food, for love and friends.
For everything thy goodness sends.

484
00:32:49.217 --> 00:32:50.378
Amen.

485
00:32:50.469 --> 00:32:51.709
- Amen!
- Amen!

486
00:32:55.390 --> 00:32:57.973
Did you know turkeys
aren't really birds?

487
00:32:58.059 --> 00:32:59.140
Why do you say that?

488
00:32:59.227 --> 00:33:02.345
They're in the pheasant family,
can't hardly fly.

489
00:33:02.439 --> 00:33:04.976
It's sad, don't you think?
Birds that can't fly?

490
00:33:05.066 --> 00:33:07.273
I love birds that can't fly.

491
00:33:07.360 --> 00:33:09.397
They are so delicious.

492
00:33:10.530 --> 00:33:12.988
- That's terrible.
- QUEENIE: I have something to tell y'all

493
00:33:13.074 --> 00:33:16.283
while we're giving thanks
for God's blessings.

494
00:33:16.369 --> 00:33:18.326
I had a miracle happen.

495
00:33:18.788 --> 00:33:21.450
The Lord saw fit to
answer my prayers.

496
00:33:25.128 --> 00:33:27.460
What does she mean,
answered her prayers?

497
00:33:27.547 --> 00:33:29.083
Thanks. Thank you.

498
00:33:29.174 --> 00:33:31.586
She's gonna have a baby, silly.

499
00:33:32.511 --> 00:33:35.503
That's what my mama said
when I was gonna have a baby brother,

500
00:33:35.597 --> 00:33:37.929
but he didn't live long,

501
00:33:39.100 --> 00:33:41.467
'cause he didn't breathe right.

502
00:33:44.314 --> 00:33:48.353
"In the afternoon, when he
had got his beautiful hind legs

503
00:33:48.443 --> 00:33:52.061
"just as Big God Nqong had promised.

504
00:33:52.906 --> 00:33:55.113
"You can see that it is 5:00,

505
00:33:55.200 --> 00:33:59.194
"because Big God Nqong's
clock says so."

506
00:33:59.287 --> 00:34:01.119
Isn't that something?

507
00:34:01.665 --> 00:34:03.030
Again, read it again.

508
00:34:03.124 --> 00:34:05.456
Oh, read it again, please.

509
00:34:05.544 --> 00:34:08.878
All right.
But afterwards, you must go to bed.

510
00:34:09.214 --> 00:34:10.625
I promise.

511
00:34:12.592 --> 00:34:14.458
"Old Man Kangaroo."

512
00:34:18.723 --> 00:34:20.430
DAISY: (WHISPERING)
Are you sleeping?

513
00:34:21.935 --> 00:34:23.425
(WHISPERING) Who's that?

514
00:34:23.520 --> 00:34:25.136
It's me, Daisy.

515
00:34:26.147 --> 00:34:27.637
(WHISPERING) Oh, hi!

516
00:34:28.191 --> 00:34:29.727
(WHISPERING) 'Kay, come on.

517
00:34:40.829 --> 00:34:42.615
BENJAMIN: (WHISPERING)
Where are we going?

518
00:34:43.748 --> 00:34:46.581
DAISY: (WHISPERING)
Come on. Under here.

519
00:34:54.134 --> 00:34:56.000
(MATCH STRIKING)

520
00:34:56.094 --> 00:34:57.550
DAISY: Here, you light it.

521
00:34:57.637 --> 00:34:59.753
BENJAMIN: I'm not supposed
to play with matches.

522
00:34:59.848 --> 00:35:02.135
DAISY: Don't be a chicken. Light it.

523
00:35:13.194 --> 00:35:16.152
DAISY: I'll tell you a secret
if you'll tell me one.

524
00:35:16.239 --> 00:35:17.695
BENJAMIN: Okay.

525
00:35:17.782 --> 00:35:21.150
DAISY: I saw my mama
kissing another man.

526
00:35:21.536 --> 00:35:23.618
Her face was red from it.

527
00:35:25.874 --> 00:35:27.364
Your turn.

528
00:35:30.670 --> 00:35:32.957
I'm not as old as I look.

529
00:35:33.048 --> 00:35:34.664
I thought so.

530
00:35:36.593 --> 00:35:39.051
You don't seem like an old person.

531
00:35:39.721 --> 00:35:41.883
- Like my grandma.
- I'm not.

532
00:35:43.642 --> 00:35:45.258
Are you sick?

533
00:35:45.810 --> 00:35:48.973
Well, I heard Mama
and Tizzy whispering.

534
00:35:49.064 --> 00:35:53.274
They said I was gonna die soon,
but maybe not.

535
00:35:55.487 --> 00:35:57.069
You're odd.

536
00:35:57.781 --> 00:36:00.694
You're different
than anybody I've ever met.

537
00:36:03.828 --> 00:36:06.035
- May I?
- Okay.

538
00:36:13.254 --> 00:36:15.666
What are you doing under there?

539
00:36:15.757 --> 00:36:19.216
You come right out here
and get back up to bed!

540
00:36:19.302 --> 00:36:21.088
It's after midnight!

541
00:36:21.179 --> 00:36:23.295
You are not to be playing together.

542
00:36:23.390 --> 00:36:24.926
DAISY: Yes, ma'am.

543
00:36:25.016 --> 00:36:27.178
FULLER: Now you get
back to bed, little lady.

544
00:36:27.268 --> 00:36:31.262
You're too young to be wandering
around in the night on your own.

545
00:36:33.942 --> 00:36:37.776
And you ought
to be ashamed of yourself.

546
00:36:48.915 --> 00:36:50.280
(QUEENIE SIGHING)

547
00:36:53.044 --> 00:36:55.126
You are a different child.

548
00:36:55.880 --> 00:36:56.995
A man-child.

549
00:36:57.090 --> 00:37:01.584
And, baby, people aren't gonna
understand just how different you are.

550
00:37:02.429 --> 00:37:04.511
(CRYING)

551
00:37:07.851 --> 00:37:10.058
What's wrong with me, Mama?

552
00:37:10.979 --> 00:37:12.765
Come here.

553
00:37:14.899 --> 00:37:17.140
God hasn't said yet, baby.

554
00:37:21.573 --> 00:37:25.111
Now go on to bed, hear?
And behave yourself.

555
00:37:26.411 --> 00:37:28.994
Go on. Say your prayers, hear?

556
00:37:39.591 --> 00:37:40.706
(CLEARING THROAT)

557
00:37:40.800 --> 00:37:44.885
DAWS: Did I ever tell you I've been
struck by lightning seven times?

558
00:37:47.182 --> 00:37:50.140
Once when I was repairing
a leak on the roof.

559
00:37:54.189 --> 00:37:57.477
Once I was just crossing
the road to get the mail.

560
00:37:58.860 --> 00:38:00.350
(EXHALING)

561
00:38:13.500 --> 00:38:14.786
<i>BENJAMIN: I never forgot her...</i>

562
00:38:14.876 --> 00:38:16.412
"...blue eyes."

563
00:38:17.879 --> 00:38:19.461
Mom?

564
00:38:19.547 --> 00:38:24.337
Did you get that this Benjamin loved you
from the first time that he saw you?

565
00:38:25.553 --> 00:38:28.045
Not many people experience that.

566
00:38:29.516 --> 00:38:31.302
Want me to go on?

567
00:38:33.269 --> 00:38:35.306
He crosses something out.

568
00:38:35.396 --> 00:38:38.684
<i>BENJAMIN: When that baby came,
things were different.</i>

569
00:38:38.775 --> 00:38:42.143
(SINGING) <i>Your mama gone away
And your daddy gonna stay</i>

570
00:38:42.237 --> 00:38:46.071
<i>Didn't leave nobody but the baby</i>

571
00:38:47.492 --> 00:38:50.109
<i>BENJAMIN: Babies were born,
people died.</i>

572
00:38:50.995 --> 00:38:52.598
<i>A lot of folks been
through that old house.</i>

573
00:38:52.622 --> 00:38:53.953
(KNOCK ON DOOR)

574
00:38:55.792 --> 00:38:59.035
I've come to say goodbye.
I'm going away.

575
00:38:59.128 --> 00:39:00.414
Going?

576
00:39:00.922 --> 00:39:02.458
Where?

577
00:39:02.549 --> 00:39:04.131
I haven't figured that out yet,

578
00:39:04.217 --> 00:39:06.675
but I'll send you a postcard
when I get there.

579
00:39:06.761 --> 00:39:09.549
What about your friend,
the tall lady?

580
00:39:09.639 --> 00:39:11.050
We are not friends anymore.

581
00:39:11.140 --> 00:39:14.428
That's what happens
with tall people sometimes.

582
00:39:14.519 --> 00:39:17.307
Well, goodbye.

583
00:39:36.583 --> 00:39:39.291
<i>BENJAMIN: Spent a lot of time
by myself that year.</i>

584
00:39:39.419 --> 00:39:40.500
(IMITATING GUN FIRING)

585
00:39:40.587 --> 00:39:41.827
Hello?

586
00:39:43.715 --> 00:39:45.501
- Hi.
- I'm moving in today.

587
00:39:45.592 --> 00:39:48.425
Welcome. We've been expecting you.

588
00:39:48.511 --> 00:39:51.549
Can you please show her up
to Mrs. Rousseau's old room?

589
00:39:51.639 --> 00:39:55.007
I'm sorry, but we usually
don't allow dogs in the house.

590
00:39:55.101 --> 00:39:58.093
Well, she's old as the hills.
She's almost blind.

591
00:39:58.187 --> 00:40:01.145
She won't be a bother much longer.

592
00:40:01.232 --> 00:40:04.941
Well, all right,
long as she stays from up underfoot.

593
00:40:05.028 --> 00:40:06.297
BENJAMIN: Right this way, ma'am.

594
00:40:06.321 --> 00:40:09.484
<i>BENJAMIN: As hard as I try,
I can't remember her name.</i>

595
00:40:09.574 --> 00:40:12.737
<i>Mrs. Lawson, or Mrs. Hartford.</i>

596
00:40:13.745 --> 00:40:15.531
<i>Maybe it was Maple.</i>

597
00:40:15.622 --> 00:40:17.954
<i>It's funny how sometimes the
people we remember the least</i>

598
00:40:18.041 --> 00:40:20.624
<i>make the greatest impression on us.</i>

599
00:40:21.169 --> 00:40:23.536
<i>I do remember she wore diamonds.</i>

600
00:40:23.630 --> 00:40:27.419
<i>And she always dressed in fine
clothing, as if she was going out.</i>

601
00:40:27.508 --> 00:40:31.126
<i>Although she never did
and nobody ever came to visit her.</i>

602
00:40:32.847 --> 00:40:35.179
<i>She taught me to play the piano.</i>

603
00:40:40.521 --> 00:40:43.183
It's not about how well you play.

604
00:40:43.900 --> 00:40:46.767
It's how you feel about
what you're playing.

605
00:40:46.861 --> 00:40:48.192
Try this.

606
00:41:04.545 --> 00:41:07.788
You can't help putting yourself
in the music.

607
00:41:15.848 --> 00:41:17.839
<i>BENJAMIN: There were many changes.</i>

608
00:41:17.934 --> 00:41:21.052
<i>Some you could see,
some you couldn't.</i>

609
00:41:22.146 --> 00:41:25.013
<i>Hair had started growing
in all sorts of places,</i>

610
00:41:25.525 --> 00:41:27.516
<i>along with other things.</i>

611
00:41:28.778 --> 00:41:31.566
<i>I felt pretty good, considering.</i>

612
00:41:32.573 --> 00:41:35.281
Darling, the pain.

613
00:41:35.368 --> 00:41:38.110
All right, Mom, I'll get the nurse.

614
00:41:38.204 --> 00:41:39.660
<i>(WOMAN CHATTERING ON TV)</i>

615
00:41:40.415 --> 00:41:43.157
<i>Look at this eye.
This is a major hurricane,</i>

616
00:41:43.251 --> 00:41:46.209
<i>a slow hurricane,
with maximum sustained winds of...</i>

617
00:41:46.295 --> 00:41:48.161
Not doing too good?

618
00:41:49.007 --> 00:41:52.295
Nobody seems to know
whether to stay or leave.

619
00:41:52.385 --> 00:41:54.672
I'm gonna ride it out.

620
00:41:54.762 --> 00:41:57.675
There.
That should make things much easier.

621
00:42:01.102 --> 00:42:04.311
Have you had a chance
to say your goodbyes?

622
00:42:04.397 --> 00:42:07.890
My father waited four hours for
my brother to get here from Boger City.

623
00:42:07.984 --> 00:42:09.975
Couldn't go without him.

624
00:42:10.486 --> 00:42:13.194
- She seems like a sweet woman.
- Yeah.

625
00:42:13.823 --> 00:42:15.592
I haven't had as much
time with her as I would've...

626
00:42:15.616 --> 00:42:17.527
- You busy? I could use your help.
- Excuse me.

627
00:42:17.618 --> 00:42:18.904
Sure.

628
00:42:19.120 --> 00:42:20.656
<i>(WOMAN CHATTERING ON PA)</i>

629
00:42:25.001 --> 00:42:26.583
<i>(TV PLAYING)</i>

630
00:42:37.055 --> 00:42:39.092
"Queenie would let
me go with Mr. Daws..."

631
00:42:39.182 --> 00:42:43.016
<i>BENJAMIN: ...to Poverty Point to watch
the boats go up and down the river.</i>

632
00:42:43.102 --> 00:42:45.059
<i>These were hard times.</i>

633
00:42:48.066 --> 00:42:51.809
Did I ever tell you I was struck
by lightning seven times?

634
00:42:52.695 --> 00:42:56.154
Once when I was in the field,
just tending to my cows.

635
00:42:58.659 --> 00:43:00.149
(PEOPLE CHATTERING)

636
00:43:00.286 --> 00:43:01.822
(SEAGULLS CAWING)

637
00:43:02.663 --> 00:43:04.950
My fourth hand didn't show up.

638
00:43:07.168 --> 00:43:10.661
Anybody want to make $2
for a day's work 'round here?

639
00:43:12.548 --> 00:43:14.255
What's the matter?

640
00:43:14.342 --> 00:43:17.130
Nobody wants to do an honest
day's work for an honest day's pay?

641
00:43:17.220 --> 00:43:18.802
He never pays.

642
00:43:20.223 --> 00:43:22.555
- Nobody wants a job?
- I do.

643
00:43:24.185 --> 00:43:26.096
You got your sea legs about you,
old man?

644
00:43:26.187 --> 00:43:27.348
Mmm-hmm.

645
00:43:28.106 --> 00:43:29.517
I think.

646
00:43:33.444 --> 00:43:35.902
Well, that's good enough for me.

647
00:43:35.988 --> 00:43:39.481
Get your ass on board.
We'll sure as hell find out.

648
00:43:44.956 --> 00:43:46.617
<i>BENJAMIN: I was as
happy as I could be.</i>

649
00:43:46.707 --> 00:43:47.947
I need a volunteer!

650
00:43:48.042 --> 00:43:49.407
<i>I would do anything.</i>

651
00:43:49.502 --> 00:43:50.958
Yes, Captain!

652
00:43:51.045 --> 00:43:53.377
Scrape off all this bird shit!

653
00:43:54.048 --> 00:43:55.789
Right away, sir.

654
00:43:56.592 --> 00:44:01.086
<i>And! was actually gonna be paid for
something I would've done for free.</i>

655
00:44:02.723 --> 00:44:05.090
<i>His name was Captain Mike Clark.</i>

656
00:44:06.060 --> 00:44:09.018
<i>He'd been on a tugboat
since he was seven.</i>

657
00:44:10.022 --> 00:44:11.763
Get moving, then.

658
00:44:12.692 --> 00:44:14.182
Come here.

659
00:44:14.277 --> 00:44:16.143
(BOAT ENGINE CHUGGING)

660
00:44:16.237 --> 00:44:19.400
Can you still get it up?

661
00:44:20.741 --> 00:44:22.732
I do every morning.

662
00:44:23.411 --> 00:44:26.824
The old pole, huh?
The high, hard one?

663
00:44:27.415 --> 00:44:28.746
I guess.

664
00:44:31.335 --> 00:44:33.997
When was the last
time you had a woman?

665
00:44:36.507 --> 00:44:38.418
- Never.
- Never?

666
00:44:38.926 --> 00:44:41.008
Not that I know of, sir.

667
00:44:41.470 --> 00:44:43.256
Wait a minute, now.

668
00:44:44.056 --> 00:44:48.175
You mean to say you've been
on this earth however many years

669
00:44:48.269 --> 00:44:51.603
and you've never had a woman?

670
00:44:52.273 --> 00:44:53.638
Mmm-mmm.

671
00:44:56.235 --> 00:44:59.318
Damn, that's the saddest thing
I've ever heard in my life.

672
00:45:00.781 --> 00:45:02.021
Never?

673
00:45:02.783 --> 00:45:03.898
No.

674
00:45:06.495 --> 00:45:10.614
Well, then, by Jesus,
you are coming with me.

675
00:45:16.547 --> 00:45:18.129
(PEOPLE CHATTERING)

676
00:45:21.636 --> 00:45:23.218
What did your father do?

677
00:45:23.304 --> 00:45:25.386
I never met my father.

678
00:45:25.473 --> 00:45:27.430
You lucky bastard.

679
00:45:28.309 --> 00:45:30.971
All fathers want to
do is hold you down.

680
00:45:33.564 --> 00:45:36.977
Out on my father's boat,
workin' the two-a-day,

681
00:45:37.318 --> 00:45:39.730
this little, fat bastard.

682
00:45:39.820 --> 00:45:41.561
"Tug Irish," they called him.

683
00:45:41.656 --> 00:45:45.024
Anyway, I finally work
up the nerve and tell him,

684
00:45:45.910 --> 00:45:49.619
"I don't want to spend the rest
of my life on a goddamn tugboat."

685
00:45:49.705 --> 00:45:51.696
You know what I'm saying?

686
00:45:52.083 --> 00:45:54.745
You don't want to spend the
rest of your life on a tugboat.

687
00:45:54.835 --> 00:45:57.167
Absolutely! Damn right!

688
00:45:59.924 --> 00:46:02.541
So you know what
my father says to me?

689
00:46:03.344 --> 00:46:07.804
He says,
"Who the hell do you think you are?

690
00:46:07.890 --> 00:46:10.678
"What the hell do
you think you can do?"

691
00:46:10.935 --> 00:46:12.642
So I tell him.

692
00:46:13.229 --> 00:46:16.472
"Well, if you're asking,

693
00:46:18.693 --> 00:46:20.775
"I want to be an artist."

694
00:46:21.320 --> 00:46:23.231
He laughs.

695
00:46:23.698 --> 00:46:28.738
"An artist? God meant for you
to work a tugboat, just like me.

696
00:46:28.828 --> 00:46:31.445
"And that's exactly
what you're gonna do."

697
00:46:31.539 --> 00:46:34.827
Well, I turned myself into an artist.

698
00:46:37.253 --> 00:46:38.994
A tattoo artist!

699
00:46:39.088 --> 00:46:40.624
(PEOPLE LAUGHING)

700
00:46:41.424 --> 00:46:44.257
I put on every one of these myself.

701
00:46:46.762 --> 00:46:50.596
You have to skin me alive to
take my art away from me now.

702
00:46:51.392 --> 00:46:54.885
When I'm dead,
I'm gonna send him my arm.

703
00:46:56.147 --> 00:46:57.558
That one.

704
00:46:59.900 --> 00:47:02.517
Don't let anyone tell you different.

705
00:47:02.611 --> 00:47:05.228
You gotta do what you're meant to do.

706
00:47:05.323 --> 00:47:08.441
And I happen to be a goddamned artist.

707
00:47:09.035 --> 00:47:11.367
But you're a tugboat captain.

708
00:47:11.912 --> 00:47:13.653
Captain Mike?

709
00:47:13.748 --> 00:47:16.536
We're ready for you and your friend.

710
00:47:18.252 --> 00:47:21.290
Let's go, old timer, eh?
Break your cherry.

711
00:47:22.465 --> 00:47:25.207
- Hello, my lovelies!
- Hey, Captain.

712
00:47:25.301 --> 00:47:26.301
- Hi, Captain.
- Hi.

713
00:47:28.429 --> 00:47:29.544
- Hi.
- WOMAN: Hi.

714
00:47:29.638 --> 00:47:32.721
He gives me the willies.
That is not for me.

715
00:47:34.602 --> 00:47:36.934
How are you tonight, grandpa?

716
00:47:37.563 --> 00:47:39.725
<i>BENJAMIN: It was a night to remember.</i>

717
00:47:39.982 --> 00:47:41.768
(BOTH GRUNTING)

718
00:47:45.446 --> 00:47:49.110
What are you, Dick Tracy or something?
I've got to rest.

719
00:47:50.242 --> 00:47:51.482
BENJAMIN: Again.

720
00:47:52.787 --> 00:47:55.119
- Thank you.
- No, thank you. You have a nice night.

721
00:47:55.206 --> 00:47:57.368
- Will you be here tomorrow?
- Every night but Sunday.

722
00:47:57.458 --> 00:48:01.167
<i>BENJAMIN: It sure made me understand
the value of earning a living.</i>

723
00:48:01.796 --> 00:48:03.628
Good night, sweetie. Come back now.

724
00:48:03.714 --> 00:48:05.955
<i>BENJAMIN: Things money can buy you.</i>

725
00:48:23.609 --> 00:48:25.316
It's nasty out.

726
00:48:25.736 --> 00:48:28.649
Can I offer you a ride somewhere?

727
00:48:30.408 --> 00:48:32.695
Well, that's awfully kind of you, sir.

728
00:48:42.002 --> 00:48:44.494
My name is Thomas, Thomas Button.

729
00:48:45.172 --> 00:48:47.288
- I'm Benjamin.
- Benjamin.

730
00:48:48.509 --> 00:48:50.671
It's a pleasure to know you.

731
00:48:52.179 --> 00:48:55.422
Would you like to stop
somewhere and have a drink?

732
00:48:55.516 --> 00:48:56.927
All right.

733
00:48:58.185 --> 00:49:00.517
Evening, Mr. Button.

734
00:49:00.646 --> 00:49:02.182
(PEOPLE CHATTERING)

735
00:49:05.025 --> 00:49:07.016
What'll it be, sir?

736
00:49:07.695 --> 00:49:10.778
- I'll have whatever he's having.
- Sazerac for the both of us.

737
00:49:10.865 --> 00:49:13.232
With whiskey, not brandy.

738
00:49:13.325 --> 00:49:14.815
You don't drink, do you?

739
00:49:14.910 --> 00:49:17.527
- It's a night for firsts.
- How's that?

740
00:49:17.621 --> 00:49:19.703
I've never been to a brothel, either.

741
00:49:19.790 --> 00:49:22.578
Well, it's an experience.

742
00:49:22.710 --> 00:49:25.793
It certainly is.
There's a time for everything.

743
00:49:25.880 --> 00:49:28.338
- True enough.
- WAITER: Your drinks.

744
00:49:29.967 --> 00:49:35.212
I don't mean to be rude, but your hands.
Is that painful?

745
00:49:35.514 --> 00:49:38.131
Well, I was born
with some form of disease.

746
00:49:38.225 --> 00:49:39.807
What kind of disease?

747
00:49:39.894 --> 00:49:41.680
I was born old.

748
00:49:43.189 --> 00:49:44.896
- I'm sorry.
- No need to be.

749
00:49:44.982 --> 00:49:47.565
There's nothing wrong with old age.

750
00:49:51.822 --> 00:49:55.031
(COUGHING)

751
00:49:56.410 --> 00:49:59.448
My wife passed away many years ago.

752
00:50:00.831 --> 00:50:02.697
BENJAMIN: (SLURRING)
I'm so, so sorry.

753
00:50:04.126 --> 00:50:06.037
She died in childbirth.

754
00:50:09.507 --> 00:50:12.090
- To children.
- To mothers.

755
00:50:16.889 --> 00:50:19.176
What line of work you in, Mr. Button?

756
00:50:19.266 --> 00:50:23.430
Buttons. Button's Buttons.
There isn't a button that we don't make.

757
00:50:25.606 --> 00:50:27.973
Our biggest competition
is B. F. Goodrich

758
00:50:28.067 --> 00:50:29.808
and his infernal zippers.

759
00:50:29.902 --> 00:50:32.690
Would you gentlemen
like anything else?

760
00:50:32.780 --> 00:50:34.862
One for the road, Benjamin?

761
00:50:34.949 --> 00:50:37.782
Only if you let me
pay for it, Mr. Button.

762
00:50:39.036 --> 00:50:41.528
So, what line of work do you do?

763
00:50:42.957 --> 00:50:45.415
I'm a tugboat man.

764
00:50:51.590 --> 00:50:53.627
I enjoyed talking to you.

765
00:50:54.093 --> 00:50:56.255
I enjoyed drinking with you.

766
00:50:59.807 --> 00:51:01.218
Benjamin?

767
00:51:01.308 --> 00:51:04.767
Would you mind if, time to time,
I stopped by and said hello?

768
00:51:04.853 --> 00:51:08.312
Anytime. Good night, Mr. Button.

769
00:51:08.816 --> 00:51:10.602
Good night, Benjamin.

770
00:51:11.318 --> 00:51:12.683
Drive on.

771
00:51:18.325 --> 00:51:19.690
Where have you been?

772
00:51:19.785 --> 00:51:24.825
Nothing. I met some people
and listened to some music.

773
00:51:27.543 --> 00:51:29.784
Oh, sweet Jesus, boy!

774
00:51:30.754 --> 00:51:33.872
<i>BENJAMIN: Growing up's a funny thing.
Sneaks up on you.</i>

775
00:51:34.800 --> 00:51:39.169
<i>One person is there, then suddenly
somebody else has taken her place.</i>

776
00:51:39.722 --> 00:51:41.429
<i>She wasn't all elbows
and knees anymore.</i>

777
00:51:41.515 --> 00:51:43.222
Benjamin! Come on!

778
00:51:43.559 --> 00:51:44.970
Okay.

779
00:51:46.186 --> 00:51:47.831
<i>BENJAMIN: I loved those
weekends when she'd come</i>

780
00:51:47.855 --> 00:51:50.688
<i>and spend the night
with her grandmother.</i>

781
00:51:58.741 --> 00:52:00.948
BENJAMIN: (WHISPERING)
Daisy. Daisy.

782
00:52:01.035 --> 00:52:02.321
(FULLER SNORING)

783
00:52:02.411 --> 00:52:04.573
You want to see something?

784
00:52:05.706 --> 00:52:10.542
You gotta keep it a secret,
so get dressed. I'll meet you out back.

785
00:52:15.341 --> 00:52:17.378
(SHUSHING) Come on.

786
00:52:19.219 --> 00:52:22.337
- Can you swim?
- I can do anything you can do.

787
00:52:22.431 --> 00:52:25.048
Here, put this on. We gotta hurry.

788
00:52:25.142 --> 00:52:26.598
(HENS CLUCKING)

789
00:52:29.188 --> 00:52:31.555
(BOAT HORN BLOWING)

790
00:52:37.988 --> 00:52:39.524
DAISY: Is he okay?

791
00:52:39.615 --> 00:52:41.071
Captain?

792
00:52:42.701 --> 00:52:44.237
Captain Mike?

793
00:52:44.912 --> 00:52:46.573
(SEAGULLS CAWING)

794
00:52:47.915 --> 00:52:50.657
Morning, Captain.
Can you take us out?

795
00:52:51.794 --> 00:52:54.126
Do you know what day it is?

796
00:52:54.213 --> 00:52:55.499
BENJAMIN: Sunday?

797
00:52:55.589 --> 00:52:57.751
Do you know what that means?

798
00:52:59.051 --> 00:53:01.463
Means I was very drunk last night.

799
00:53:02.054 --> 00:53:04.341
Well, you're drunk every night.

800
00:53:06.767 --> 00:53:09.099
- Is that a girl?
- Close friend.

801
00:53:09.770 --> 00:53:10.930
I want to show her the river.

802
00:53:10.979 --> 00:53:14.313
You're not supposed to
go joyriding with civilians.

803
00:53:15.442 --> 00:53:17.604
I could lose my license.

804
00:53:22.032 --> 00:53:23.614
(GRUNTING)

805
00:53:27.413 --> 00:53:28.903
What are you waiting for?

806
00:53:29.581 --> 00:53:31.288
(BOAT HORN BLOWS)

807
00:53:31.625 --> 00:53:33.332
(ENGINE CHUGGING)

808
00:53:46.056 --> 00:53:48.639
(SHIP HORN BLOWING)

809
00:53:59.069 --> 00:54:02.187
MIKE: Pulled in for repair
a wounded duck.

810
00:54:03.615 --> 00:54:05.777
She's flying now, huh?

811
00:54:06.285 --> 00:54:07.946
MAN: Ahoy, sailor!

812
00:54:12.499 --> 00:54:14.831
I wish we could go with them.

813
00:54:20.841 --> 00:54:23.128
Did you say something, Morn?

814
00:54:24.803 --> 00:54:27.090
(PEOPLE CHATTERING)

815
00:54:28.348 --> 00:54:30.760
(THUNDER CRASHING)

816
00:54:30.851 --> 00:54:32.842
It's getting really bad.

817
00:54:34.855 --> 00:54:36.641
Can you hear me, Mom?

818
00:54:36.732 --> 00:54:37.813
(MOANS)

819
00:54:37.900 --> 00:54:39.186
Huh?

820
00:54:39.276 --> 00:54:41.984
Time just seeped out of me.

821
00:54:43.739 --> 00:54:45.104
(DAISY MOANING)

822
00:54:48.702 --> 00:54:50.534
"Things were changing quickly."

823
00:54:50.621 --> 00:54:54.740
I don't know how it's possible,
but you seem to have more hair.

824
00:54:56.251 --> 00:54:59.243
What if I told you
that I wasn't getting older,

825
00:54:59.338 --> 00:55:02.626
but I was getting younger
than everybody else?

826
00:55:02.716 --> 00:55:06.630
Well, I'd feel sorry for you,

827
00:55:06.720 --> 00:55:09.587
to have to see everybody
you love die before you do.

828
00:55:09.681 --> 00:55:11.592
It's an awful responsibility.

829
00:55:11.683 --> 00:55:15.267
<i>BENJAMIN: I'd never thought about
life or death that way before.</i>

830
00:55:16.897 --> 00:55:20.982
Benjamin, we're meant
to lose the people we love.

831
00:55:21.401 --> 00:55:24.814
How else would we know
how important they are to us?

832
00:55:27.908 --> 00:55:32.402
<i>BENJAMIN: And one fall day, a familiar
visitor came knocking on our door.</i>

833
00:55:34.081 --> 00:55:36.914
You want to go with
me to the drugstore?

834
00:55:47.052 --> 00:55:49.419
<i>BENJAMIN: She taught me
how to play the piano.</i>

835
00:55:49.513 --> 00:55:50.799
- Amen.
- Amen.

836
00:55:50.889 --> 00:55:54.098
<i>BENJAMIN: And she taught me
what it meant to miss somebody.</i>

837
00:55:58.605 --> 00:56:00.095
Let's go.

838
00:56:01.108 --> 00:56:03.019
<i>BENJAMIN: I had gone to a brothel.</i>

839
00:56:03.110 --> 00:56:05.442
<i>I'd had my first drink.</i>

840
00:56:05.529 --> 00:56:09.022
<i>Said goodbye to one friend
and buried another.</i>

841
00:56:09.533 --> 00:56:14.403
<i>In 1936, when I was coming to the end
of the 17th year of my life,</i>

842
00:56:14.496 --> 00:56:17.363
<i>I packed my bag, said goodbye.</i>

843
00:56:17.457 --> 00:56:19.789
- Bye, Benjamin.
- BENJAMIN: Goodbye.

844
00:56:19.877 --> 00:56:24.371
<i>BENJAMIN: I knew, life being what it
was, I'd probably never see them again.</i>

845
00:56:26.550 --> 00:56:28.211
MAN: Bye, Mr. Benjamin.

846
00:56:28.302 --> 00:56:30.794
- Good luck to you, son.
- Thank you.

847
00:56:35.309 --> 00:56:38.222
- I love you, Mama.
- I love you, too, baby.

848
00:56:39.396 --> 00:56:42.639
I want you to say your
prayers every night, hear?

849
00:56:47.487 --> 00:56:49.569
Be safe, hear?

850
00:57:00.959 --> 00:57:02.324
DAISY: Benjamin!

851
00:57:05.422 --> 00:57:08.084
- Where you going?
- To sea.

852
00:57:09.468 --> 00:57:11.550
I'll send you a postcard.

853
00:57:13.347 --> 00:57:15.304
From everywhere.

854
00:57:15.390 --> 00:57:18.007
Write me a postcard from everywhere.

855
00:57:32.532 --> 00:57:34.398
DAISY: Can you imagine?

856
00:57:36.787 --> 00:57:42.908
He sent me a postcard
from everywhere he went.

857
00:57:44.461 --> 00:57:46.452
Every place he worked.

858
00:57:47.756 --> 00:57:50.874
Newfoundland. Baffin Bay.

859
00:57:51.426 --> 00:57:54.544
Glasgow. Liverpool. Narvik.

860
00:57:55.305 --> 00:58:00.050
He had gone with that Captain Mike.

861
00:58:02.062 --> 00:58:04.303
<i>BENJAMIN: Captain Mike had
contracted for three years</i>

862
00:58:04.398 --> 00:58:06.730
<i>with Moran Brothers Tug and Salvage.</i>

863
00:58:06.817 --> 00:58:10.685
<i>The old ship had been refitted with
a diesel engine and a new sea winch.</i>

864
00:58:10.779 --> 00:58:13.692
<i>We went around Florida
and up the Atlantic seaboard.</i>

865
00:58:13.782 --> 00:58:17.195
<i>We were a crew of seven now.
Captain Mike and me.</i>

866
00:58:17.285 --> 00:58:20.653
<i>Cookie, Prentiss Ma yes
from Wilmington, Delaware.</i>

867
00:58:20.747 --> 00:58:23.159
<i>The Brody twins, Rick and Vic,</i>

868
00:58:23.250 --> 00:58:25.491
<i>who got along fine at sea
but, for some reason,</i>

869
00:58:25.585 --> 00:58:28.668
<i>once they were on dry land
couldn't stand the sight of each other.</i>

870
00:58:28.755 --> 00:58:32.339
You know, one in every
eight boats never returns.

871
00:58:32.426 --> 00:58:34.546
<i>BENJAMIN: There was John Grimm,
who sure fit his name.</i>

872
00:58:34.636 --> 00:58:36.502
All hands lost at sea.

873
00:58:36.596 --> 00:58:38.837
<i>BENJAMIN: From Belvedere,
South Dakota.</i>

874
00:58:40.225 --> 00:58:43.058
<i>And Pleasant Curtis
from Asheville, Notch.</i>

875
00:58:43.145 --> 00:58:46.354
<i>Never said a word to anyone,
except himself.</i>

876
00:58:48.442 --> 00:58:51.355
I wrote him constantly.

877
00:58:52.946 --> 00:58:57.986
<i>DAISY: I told him I had been Invited
to audition in New York City</i>

878
00:58:58.535 --> 00:59:01.197
<i>for the School of American Ballet.</i>

879
00:59:01.288 --> 00:59:02.699
Please stay.

880
00:59:02.789 --> 00:59:04.951
Thank you. Thank you.

881
00:59:06.918 --> 00:59:08.204
You can stay.

882
00:59:10.672 --> 00:59:13.790
<i>DAISY: But I was relegated
to the corps.</i>

883
00:59:14.092 --> 00:59:16.459
<i>Another dancing gypsy.</i>

884
00:59:20.766 --> 00:59:22.302
MIKE: Benjamin!

885
00:59:22.934 --> 00:59:25.392
How is it when you showed up

886
00:59:25.479 --> 00:59:29.393
you were no bigger than a bollard
with one foot in the grave,

887
00:59:29.483 --> 00:59:33.693
but now, either I drink a hell
of a lot more than I think I do,

888
00:59:34.946 --> 00:59:36.607
or you sprouted?

889
00:59:37.491 --> 00:59:39.277
What's your secret?

890
00:59:40.660 --> 00:59:42.276
Well, Captain,

891
00:59:44.039 --> 00:59:45.871
you do drink a lot.

892
00:59:47.334 --> 00:59:49.245
(BOTH LAUGHING)

893
00:59:50.670 --> 00:59:54.914
<i>BENJAMIN: We stayed in a small hotel
with a grand name, The Winter Palace.</i>

894
00:59:55.008 --> 00:59:57.796
MIKE: You have no idea
what you're talking about.

895
00:59:57.886 --> 01:00:01.379
The hummingbird is
not just another bird.

896
01:00:02.099 --> 01:00:05.808
Its heart rate's 1,200 beats per minute.

897
01:00:05.894 --> 01:00:07.476
(MAN TRANSLATING INTO RUSSIAN)

898
01:00:07.562 --> 01:00:10.270
Its wings beat 80 times a second.

899
01:00:10.357 --> 01:00:12.098
(MAN TRANSLATING INTO RUSSIAN)

900
01:00:12.192 --> 01:00:15.230
If you was to stop
their wings from beating,

901
01:00:15.862 --> 01:00:17.899
it would be dead in
less than 10 seconds.

902
01:00:17.989 --> 01:00:19.605
(MAN TRANSLATING INTO RUSSIAN)

903
01:00:19.699 --> 01:00:22.361
This is no ordinary bird.

904
01:00:23.036 --> 01:00:25.152
This is a frickin' miracle.

905
01:00:28.291 --> 01:00:32.205
They slowed down their
wings with moving pictures,

906
01:00:32.879 --> 01:00:35.086
and you know what they saw?

907
01:00:35.549 --> 01:00:38.382
Their wingtips are doing that.

908
01:00:42.389 --> 01:00:46.257
You know what the figure eight
is the mathematical symbol for?

909
01:00:49.229 --> 01:00:50.811
(WHISPERING) Infinity.

910
01:00:50.897 --> 01:00:52.228
Infinity!

911
01:00:52.399 --> 01:00:53.399
(ALL LAUGHING)

912
01:00:55.735 --> 01:00:58.648
<i>BENJAMIN: Everybody, no matter
what differences they had,</i>

913
01:00:58.738 --> 01:01:02.777
<i>the languages, the color of their skin,
had one thing in common.</i>

914
01:01:03.702 --> 01:01:06.069
<i>They were drunk every single night.</i>

915
01:01:06.163 --> 01:01:07.699
Three, please.

916
01:01:07.789 --> 01:01:09.405
Could you hold, dear, for us, please?

917
01:01:09.499 --> 01:01:11.786
Thank you very much. Good evening.

918
01:01:11.877 --> 01:01:14.585
<i>BENJAMIN: Her name
was Elizabeth Abbott.</i>

919
01:01:14.671 --> 01:01:18.005
<i>She was not beautiful.
She was plain as paper.</i>

920
01:01:18.091 --> 01:01:20.924
<i>But she was pretty
as any picture to me.</i>

921
01:01:22.179 --> 01:01:24.261
What are you looking at?

922
01:01:26.433 --> 01:01:29.016
If you must know,
we have a longstanding agreement

923
01:01:29.102 --> 01:01:30.467
never to go to bed sober.

924
01:01:30.562 --> 01:01:32.974
- Isn't that right, darling?
- Whatever you say, darling.

925
01:01:33.064 --> 01:01:35.146
<i>BENJAMIN: Her husband
was Walter Abbott.</i>

926
01:01:35.233 --> 01:01:39.147
<i>He was Chief Minister of the
British Trade Mission in Murmansk,</i>

927
01:01:39.237 --> 01:01:40.853
<i>and he was a spy.</i>

928
01:01:40.947 --> 01:01:43.860
- Darling.
- Oh, thank you, my darling.

929
01:01:43.950 --> 01:01:45.987
- Key, darling.
- Oh, yes.

930
01:01:50.457 --> 01:01:53.540
I broke my heel off one of my shoes.

931
01:01:53.627 --> 01:01:57.245
I'm not in the habit of walking
about in my stocking feet.

932
01:02:01.635 --> 01:02:03.797
<i>BENJAMIN: They were long days there.</i>

933
01:02:11.311 --> 01:02:13.302
<i>And even longer nights.</i>

934
01:02:15.482 --> 01:02:19.066
<i>One particular night,
I was having trouble sleeping.</i>

935
01:02:20.487 --> 01:02:22.023
I'm sorry.

936
01:02:23.865 --> 01:02:25.651
I couldn't sleep.

937
01:02:38.505 --> 01:02:41.998
I was gonna make some tea.
Would you like some?

938
01:02:42.884 --> 01:02:44.750
Oh, no. Thank you.

939
01:03:04.739 --> 01:03:05.945
(WATER RUNNING)

940
01:03:22.549 --> 01:03:24.165
Milk? Honey?

941
01:03:24.759 --> 01:03:26.716
A bit of honey, please.

942
01:03:27.220 --> 01:03:29.006
I hope you like flies in your honey.

943
01:03:29.097 --> 01:03:30.804
Oh, perhaps not.

944
01:03:45.613 --> 01:03:49.902
Oh, maybe better
to let it steep a little.

945
01:03:50.869 --> 01:03:52.075
Steep?

946
01:03:52.412 --> 01:03:53.527
Soak.

947
01:03:53.747 --> 01:03:57.456
I don't know, I mean,
there's a proper way of making tea.

948
01:03:57.542 --> 01:04:00.785
Well, where I'm from,
people just want it to be hot.

949
01:04:00.879 --> 01:04:02.995
Well, quite right.

950
01:04:11.890 --> 01:04:14.302
- Now, you're a seaman.
- A sailor.

951
01:04:14.392 --> 01:04:17.134
I hope you won't think me impolite,
but I have to ask,

952
01:04:17.228 --> 01:04:19.344
aren't you a little old
to be working on a boat?

953
01:04:19.439 --> 01:04:22.306
There's no age limit,
as long as you can do the work.

954
01:04:22.400 --> 01:04:23.400
Oh!

955
01:04:33.661 --> 01:04:35.993
And you have trouble sleeping?
Thank you.

956
01:04:36.081 --> 01:04:39.290
I didn't think I did.
I usually sleep like a baby.

957
01:04:40.251 --> 01:04:42.709
Something's been keeping me up.

958
01:04:43.922 --> 01:04:45.128
My father, in his 80s,

959
01:04:45.215 --> 01:04:48.503
he was so convinced
he was gonna die in his sleep,

960
01:04:49.135 --> 01:04:52.298
he limited himself
to having afternoon naps.

961
01:04:53.014 --> 01:04:55.802
He was so determined
he was gonna cheat death.

962
01:04:56.976 --> 01:04:58.842
- Did he?
- Did he what?

963
01:04:58.978 --> 01:05:00.639
Die in his sleep?

964
01:05:02.315 --> 01:05:04.898
He died sitting in his favorite chair

965
01:05:04.984 --> 01:05:07.646
listening to his favorite
program on the wireless.

966
01:05:07.737 --> 01:05:10.229
He must have known something.

967
01:05:15.954 --> 01:05:21.040
My husband's the British Trade Minister,
and we've been here for 14 months.

968
01:05:21.126 --> 01:05:24.460
- Good God.
- We were supposed to go to Peking

969
01:05:24.546 --> 01:05:28.039
but it never seemed to work out.

970
01:05:29.509 --> 01:05:31.216
Have you been in the Far East?

971
01:05:31.302 --> 01:05:33.509
No. I've never been anywhere, really.

972
01:05:33.596 --> 01:05:36.054
I mean, outside of harbors.

973
01:05:36.141 --> 01:05:37.802
And where is it that you're from?

974
01:05:37.892 --> 01:05:40.429
New Orleans. Louisiana.

975
01:05:41.896 --> 01:05:44.228
I didn't know there was another.

976
01:05:46.526 --> 01:05:49.939
<i>BENJAMIN: And she told me
about all the places she had been,</i>

977
01:05:50.029 --> 01:05:51.565
<i>and what she had seen.</i>

978
01:05:53.158 --> 01:05:56.071
<i>And we talked till
just before the dawn.</i>

979
01:05:57.078 --> 01:05:58.568
I'm just a lush, myself.

980
01:05:58.663 --> 01:06:03.624
<i>And we went back to our rooms,
to our separate lives.</i>

981
01:06:09.048 --> 01:06:12.382
<i>But every night,
we'd meet again in that lobby.</i>

982
01:06:17.682 --> 01:06:21.596
<i>A hotel in the middle of the
night can be a magical place.</i>

983
01:06:24.439 --> 01:06:26.976
<i>A mouse running, and stopping.</i>

984
01:06:27.066 --> 01:06:28.066
(FEET PATTERING)

985
01:06:28.776 --> 01:06:30.141
<i>A radiator hissing.</i>

986
01:06:30.236 --> 01:06:31.772
(HISSING)

987
01:06:31.905 --> 01:06:33.771
<i>A curtain blowing.</i>

988
01:06:34.908 --> 01:06:36.569
(WIND BLOWING)

989
01:06:37.535 --> 01:06:40.903
<i>There's something peaceful,
even comforting</i>

990
01:06:40.997 --> 01:06:44.240
<i>knowing that the people you
love are asleep in their beds</i>

991
01:06:44.334 --> 01:06:46.575
<i>where nothing can harm them.</i>

992
01:06:49.672 --> 01:06:52.630
<i>Elizabeth and I would
lose track of the night</i>

993
01:06:53.134 --> 01:06:55.341
<i>until just before daybreak.</i>

994
01:06:57.931 --> 01:07:00.719
I think I may have given
you the wrong impression.

995
01:07:00.808 --> 01:07:02.344
Beg pardon?

996
01:07:02.435 --> 01:07:06.269
Well, married women
don't customarily sit around

997
01:07:06.356 --> 01:07:08.459
in the middle of the night
with strange men in hotels.

998
01:07:08.483 --> 01:07:12.067
I wouldn't know what a married
woman does or doesn't do.

999
01:07:17.784 --> 01:07:19.274
Good night.

1000
01:07:21.579 --> 01:07:22.910
Murmansk.

1001
01:07:23.289 --> 01:07:24.289
(DAISY MOANS)

1002
01:07:25.500 --> 01:07:28.583
"I've met somebody,
and I've fallen in love."

1003
01:07:28.670 --> 01:07:29.910
Mom?

1004
01:07:30.171 --> 01:07:31.707
(MOANING SOFTLY)

1005
01:07:33.716 --> 01:07:36.299
That was over 60 years ago.

1006
01:07:37.554 --> 01:07:38.589
Did you love him, Mother?

1007
01:07:38.680 --> 01:07:41.468
What does a girl know about love?

1008
01:08:15.049 --> 01:08:16.289
Well...

1009
01:08:18.761 --> 01:08:22.550
- I'm not dressed.
- Oh, you look splendid, just as you are.

1010
01:08:24.809 --> 01:08:27.892
Don't waste any time bothering about
the wine or the cheese in Murmansk,

1011
01:08:27.979 --> 01:08:31.017
'cause they're really
completely ordinary,

1012
01:08:31.107 --> 01:08:36.102
but the caviar and the vodka

1013
01:08:36.654 --> 01:08:40.773
are sublime and plentiful.

1014
01:08:44.537 --> 01:08:45.868
So.

1015
01:08:51.127 --> 01:08:52.458
Savor it.

1016
01:08:53.463 --> 01:08:54.463
Hmm.

1017
01:08:54.547 --> 01:08:56.538
And don't eat it all at once,

1018
01:08:56.633 --> 01:08:59.751
because that way,
there's nothing left to enjoy.

1019
01:09:00.219 --> 01:09:01.300
(SIGHS)

1020
01:09:01.387 --> 01:09:05.756
And now, take a little swallow of vodka
while it's still in your mouth.

1021
01:09:06.267 --> 01:09:07.974
(TOASTING IN RUSSIAN)

1022
01:09:20.615 --> 01:09:23.482
You haven't been with
many women, have you?

1023
01:09:24.661 --> 01:09:26.322
Not on Sundays.

1024
01:09:28.498 --> 01:09:30.258
And you've never had
caviar before, have you?

1025
01:09:30.333 --> 01:09:31.994
No, ma'am.

1026
01:09:37.799 --> 01:09:39.506
When I was 19,

1027
01:09:40.468 --> 01:09:46.760
I attempted to become the first woman
ever to swim the English Channel.

1028
01:09:47.767 --> 01:09:49.178
Really?

1029
01:09:49.769 --> 01:09:52.852
But the current that
day was so strong that,

1030
01:09:52.939 --> 01:09:56.057
for every stroke I took,
I was pushed back two.

1031
01:09:56.609 --> 01:09:59.271
<i>I was in the water for 32 hours.</i>

1032
01:10:00.196 --> 01:10:04.064
And when I was two miles from Calais,

1033
01:10:05.159 --> 01:10:06.945
<i>it started to rain.</i>

1034
01:10:07.620 --> 01:10:09.577
MAN: That's it! Steady on!

1035
01:10:10.081 --> 01:10:12.743
<i>When I couldn't go any further,</i>

1036
01:10:14.293 --> 01:10:15.783
I stopped.

1037
01:10:17.130 --> 01:10:18.791
<i>I just stopped.</i>

1038
01:10:19.340 --> 01:10:24.255
And everybody asked me,
would I try again?

1039
01:10:24.971 --> 01:10:26.837
<i>For why wouldn't I?</i>

1040
01:10:29.726 --> 01:10:31.467
But I never did.

1041
01:10:32.854 --> 01:10:37.143
As a matter of fact, I've never done
anything with my life after that.

1042
01:10:41.237 --> 01:10:43.319
Your hands are so coarse.

1043
01:10:53.624 --> 01:10:56.207
I can feel the wind in your cheek.

1044
01:10:57.086 --> 01:10:58.997
(CLOCK CHIMING)

1045
01:11:02.967 --> 01:11:05.504
I'm afraid it's the Witching hour.

1046
01:11:11.350 --> 01:11:14.638
<i>BENJAMIN: It was the first time
a woman had ever kissed me.</i>

1047
01:11:15.188 --> 01:11:17.600
<i>It's something you never forget.</i>

1048
01:11:25.573 --> 01:11:26.573
(CORK POPPING)

1049
01:11:26.657 --> 01:11:27.988
(ELIZABETH EXCLAIMING)

1050
01:11:28.075 --> 01:11:30.112
BENJAMIN: I think you
make me feel younger.

1051
01:11:30.203 --> 01:11:32.786
ELIZABETH: You make me
feel years younger, too.

1052
01:11:32.872 --> 01:11:34.488
I wish I was.

1053
01:11:35.458 --> 01:11:37.620
So many things I'd change.

1054
01:11:38.294 --> 01:11:40.626
I'd undo all my mistakes.

1055
01:11:40.713 --> 01:11:42.454
What mistakes?

1056
01:11:45.760 --> 01:11:47.967
I kept waiting, you know?

1057
01:11:48.554 --> 01:11:53.094
Thinking that I'd do something
to change my circumstances.

1058
01:11:54.352 --> 01:11:56.093
Do something.

1059
01:11:57.647 --> 01:12:00.890
Such an awful waste.
You never get it back.

1060
01:12:01.359 --> 01:12:02.849
Wasted time.

1061
01:12:09.116 --> 01:12:11.574
If we're going to have an affair,

1062
01:12:12.245 --> 01:12:15.112
you're never to look
at me during the day.

1063
01:12:15.748 --> 01:12:18.706
And we're always
to part before sunrise.

1064
01:12:19.335 --> 01:12:21.997
And we will never say "I love you."

1065
01:12:23.589 --> 01:12:25.421
Those are the rules.

1066
01:12:25.508 --> 01:12:26.998
(BENJAMIN SHIVERING)

1067
01:12:28.010 --> 01:12:30.172
- Are you cold?
- I'm freezing.

1068
01:12:30.263 --> 01:12:32.220
Oh, you! You're frozen.

1069
01:12:32.306 --> 01:12:35.549
What an idiot, I'm standing here
in this fur. How thoughtless of me.

1070
01:13:09.176 --> 01:13:12.009
<i>BENJAMIN: She was the first
woman that ever loved me.</i>

1071
01:13:14.974 --> 01:13:16.214
You want me to skip some?

1072
01:13:16.309 --> 01:13:22.100
No, I'm glad he had somebody
to keep him warm.

1073
01:13:25.735 --> 01:13:28.227
"I couldn't wait to see her again."

1074
01:13:28.487 --> 01:13:30.524
(PEOPLE CHATTERING)

1075
01:13:41.125 --> 01:13:43.457
<i>BENJAMIN: We saw each
other every night.</i>

1076
01:13:44.003 --> 01:13:46.335
<i>We always used the same room.</i>

1077
01:13:48.299 --> 01:13:51.667
<i>But each time seemed
new and different.</i>

1078
01:13:53.012 --> 01:13:54.502
Come here.

1079
01:14:01.938 --> 01:14:03.349
(WHISPERING) Elizabeth.

1080
01:14:04.690 --> 01:14:06.146
Good night.

1081
01:14:08.819 --> 01:14:10.480
<i>BENJAMIN: Until one night.</i>

1082
01:14:47.733 --> 01:14:53.319
<i>MAN ON RADIO:
Yesterday, December 7th, 1941,</i>

1083
01:14:53.406 --> 01:14:56.524
<i>a date which will live in infamy...</i>

1084
01:14:56.617 --> 01:15:00.781
MIKE: It's a meeting, a policy
meeting regarding your future,

1085
01:15:01.706 --> 01:15:03.288
possibly beyond.

1086
01:15:04.667 --> 01:15:07.250
There's been a change of plan, lads.

1087
01:15:07.420 --> 01:15:10.037
As you may or may not know,

1088
01:15:10.131 --> 01:15:12.748
the Japs bombed
Pearl Harbor yesterday.

1089
01:15:13.175 --> 01:15:16.668
Frank D. Roosevelt's asked
each of us to do our part.

1090
01:15:17.138 --> 01:15:21.257
The Chelsea's been commissioned
to serve in the United States Navy.

1091
01:15:21.684 --> 01:15:24.972
To repair, to salvage, and to rescue.

1092
01:15:26.480 --> 01:15:30.849
Anybody doesn't want to go to war,
now is the time to say so.

1093
01:15:30.943 --> 01:15:35.153
Once you set foot on that boat,
you're in the Navy, friend.

1094
01:15:38.367 --> 01:15:41.405
Yeah, I've been meaning
to talk with you, Mike.

1095
01:15:41.495 --> 01:15:43.532
My wife's doing poorly.

1096
01:15:43.622 --> 01:15:46.364
I'd like to maybe see
her one more time.

1097
01:15:48.085 --> 01:15:51.919
You're free to make your way
home any way you can, Mr. Mayes.

1098
01:15:57.511 --> 01:15:59.311
RICK: Well, if he's leaving,
who's gonna cook?

1099
01:15:59.388 --> 01:16:03.473
JOHN: Food poisoning's one of the
leading causes of death at sea.

1100
01:16:03.559 --> 01:16:05.926
Right after inadequate
safety equipment.

1101
01:16:06.020 --> 01:16:08.682
I can cook, Captain.
Been doing it all my life.

1102
01:16:08.773 --> 01:16:13.188
I don't know.
You're a little moody for war, Benjamin.

1103
01:16:13.277 --> 01:16:15.234
What the hell?

1104
01:16:15.321 --> 01:16:19.690
I'll take any man wants to kick the
shite out of the Japs and the Huns.

1105
01:16:21.077 --> 01:16:24.866
That's it, pack your gear.
We're going to war, gentlemen!

1106
01:16:31.712 --> 01:16:33.498
<i>BENJAMIN: She had left a note.</i>

1107
01:16:34.840 --> 01:16:37.628
<i>She wrote,
"It was nice to have met you."</i>

1108
01:16:38.344 --> 01:16:40.005
<i>And that was it.</i>

1109
01:16:43.182 --> 01:16:46.265
<i>It wasn't the war any of us expected.</i>

1110
01:16:46.352 --> 01:16:50.016
<i>We would just tow crippled ships,
scraps of metal, really.</i>

1111
01:16:50.606 --> 01:16:53.598
<i>If there was a war, we didn't see it.</i>

1112
01:16:55.486 --> 01:16:59.571
<i>There was a man assigned to us.
The Chief Gunner loved the Navy.</i>

1113
01:16:59.657 --> 01:17:01.864
<i>But most of all, he loved America.</i>

1114
01:17:01.951 --> 01:17:04.864
There is no other country in the world.

1115
01:17:04.954 --> 01:17:06.069
When you spell America...

1116
01:17:06.163 --> 01:17:10.327
<i>His name was Dennis Smith,
and he was a full-blooded Cherokee.</i>

1117
01:17:10.417 --> 01:17:13.535
<i>His family had been Americans
for over 500 years.</i>

1118
01:17:13.629 --> 01:17:18.169
These pacifists.
They say they won't fight on conscience.

1119
01:17:18.259 --> 01:17:21.877
Now, where would be
if everybody decided to act

1120
01:17:21.971 --> 01:17:25.965
- according to their conscience?
- Keep it down, would you, Chief?

1121
01:17:30.229 --> 01:17:32.061
(RATTLING)

1122
01:17:34.567 --> 01:17:37.855
(CREAKING)

1123
01:17:42.158 --> 01:17:45.696
PLEASANT: Hey.
I've been watching you.

1124
01:17:46.704 --> 01:17:48.536
You seem trustworthy.

1125
01:17:50.291 --> 01:17:52.407
If something happens to me,

1126
01:17:56.463 --> 01:17:59.046
could you see that
this gets to my wife?

1127
01:17:59.133 --> 01:18:03.718
<i>BENJAMIN: He'd given me all of his pay.
Hadn't spent a dime of it.</i>

1128
01:18:05.598 --> 01:18:08.886
I want my family to know
I was thinking about them.

1129
01:18:11.437 --> 01:18:13.519
(BELL RINGING)

1130
01:18:13.606 --> 01:18:15.472
MIKE: All hands on deck!

1131
01:18:16.859 --> 01:18:17.859
(DISTANT EXPLOSIONS)

1132
01:18:17.943 --> 01:18:20.776
Get your asses up here,
you lazy bastards!

1133
01:18:31.874 --> 01:18:33.285
(EXPLOSIONS CONTINUING)

1134
01:18:42.051 --> 01:18:44.292
<i>BENJAMIN: The war
had finally found us.</i>

1135
01:18:46.972 --> 01:18:48.462
VIC: All stop!

1136
01:18:51.143 --> 01:18:53.180
Pleasant, man that light.

1137
01:19:01.028 --> 01:19:05.238
<i>BENJAMIN: A transport carrying
1,300 men had been split by a torpedo.</i>

1138
01:19:07.618 --> 01:19:09.905
<i>We were first to arrive at the scene.</i>

1139
01:19:09.995 --> 01:19:13.579
- Cut the engines!
- All stop!

1140
01:19:18.671 --> 01:19:20.628
<i>BENJAMIN: We were the only sound.</i>

1141
01:19:34.520 --> 01:19:35.976
Fellas!

1142
01:19:38.524 --> 01:19:40.014
(ENGINE STARTING)

1143
01:19:45.906 --> 01:19:47.021
Sub!

1144
01:19:51.787 --> 01:19:54.620
MIKE: We sure as hell
can't outrun them fuckers.

1145
01:19:56.333 --> 01:19:58.665
Battle stations!

1146
01:20:08.512 --> 01:20:09.547
Thank you, Chief.

1147
01:20:11.807 --> 01:20:12.922
What?

1148
01:20:25.904 --> 01:20:27.736
VIC: Is that the last one?

1149
01:21:10.949 --> 01:21:12.280
(SCREAMING)

1150
01:21:19.083 --> 01:21:20.083
(GRUNTS)

1151
01:21:21.293 --> 01:21:22.954
(BOAT ENGINE REVVING)

1152
01:21:29.802 --> 01:21:31.292
(CRASHING)

1153
01:21:49.321 --> 01:21:50.561
BENJAMIN: Captain!

1154
01:21:54.076 --> 01:21:55.737
(BENJAMIN GRUNTING)

1155
01:21:56.245 --> 01:21:57.952
(MIKE SCREAMING)

1156
01:22:06.171 --> 01:22:08.833
They shot the hell out of my painting!

1157
01:22:10.092 --> 01:22:11.958
Give me your other hand.

1158
01:22:17.307 --> 01:22:18.410
You'll be all right, Captain.

1159
01:22:18.434 --> 01:22:22.723
They got a nice spot in Heaven
waiting for you. Nice spot.

1160
01:22:24.231 --> 01:22:27.314
You can be as mad as a mad
dog at the way things went.

1161
01:22:30.279 --> 01:22:33.988
You could swear, curse the Fates.

1162
01:22:36.243 --> 01:22:38.405
But when it comes to the end,

1163
01:22:40.581 --> 01:22:42.367
you have to let go.

1164
01:22:49.339 --> 01:22:50.579
Captain?

1165
01:23:11.403 --> 01:23:14.737
<i>BENJAMIN: Thirteen hundred and
twenty eight men died that day.</i>

1166
01:23:17.034 --> 01:23:20.277
<i>I said my goodbyes to the Cherokee,
Dennis Smith.</i>

1167
01:23:21.246 --> 01:23:24.455
<i>John Grimm, who was right,
he was gonna die there.</i>

1168
01:23:25.918 --> 01:23:28.660
<i>I sent Pleasant Curtis' wife his money.</i>

1169
01:23:29.463 --> 01:23:32.546
<i>I said goodbye to the twin, Vic Brody,</i>

1170
01:23:32.633 --> 01:23:37.343
<i>and to Mike Clark,
captain of the tugboat Chelsea.</i>

1171
01:23:39.765 --> 01:23:44.259
<i>I said goodbye to all the other men
who had dreams of their own,</i>

1172
01:23:44.353 --> 01:23:46.936
<i>all the men who wanted
to be insurance salesmen</i>

1173
01:23:47.022 --> 01:23:49.980
<i>or doctors or lawyers or Indian chiefs.</i>

1174
01:23:51.026 --> 01:23:52.858
This don't get fixed.

1175
01:23:54.947 --> 01:23:58.030
<i>Out here, death didn't seem natural.</i>

1176
01:24:02.955 --> 01:24:04.741
(HUMMINGBIRD BUZZING)

1177
01:24:15.008 --> 01:24:18.217
<i>I'd never seen a hummingbird
that far out to sea.</i>

1178
01:24:19.721 --> 01:24:21.337
<i>Before or since.</i>

1179
01:24:27.187 --> 01:24:33.433
<i>And in May of 1945,
when I was 26 years old,</i>

1180
01:24:33.527 --> 01:24:34.642
<i>I came home.</i>

1181
01:24:35.571 --> 01:24:38.188
WOMAN: I'm ready! I'm ready!

1182
01:24:38.282 --> 01:24:39.647
QUEENIE: I'm coming!

1183
01:24:40.534 --> 01:24:44.198
- WOMAN: I'm ready!
- All right, I'm coming, Miss Alfalina.

1184
01:24:44.288 --> 01:24:45.824
- Queenie?
- Yes?

1185
01:24:48.834 --> 01:24:50.416
(PEOPLE CHATTERING)

1186
01:24:50.502 --> 01:24:51.583
(EXCLAIMING LOUDLY)

1187
01:24:51.670 --> 01:24:57.586
Sweet Jesus! Oh, you're home!
Oh, Lord, you came back!

1188
01:24:58.468 --> 01:25:00.425
- Let me look at you.
- Who's that, Mama?

1189
01:25:00.512 --> 01:25:03.755
- Child, it's your brother, Benjamin.
- I didn't know he was my brother.

1190
01:25:03.849 --> 01:25:05.618
There's a shitload of things
you don't know, child.

1191
01:25:05.642 --> 01:25:06.869
Get on out there and finish sweeping.

1192
01:25:06.893 --> 01:25:09.163
Come here, wash your hands,
help me with the table. Go on, now.

1193
01:25:09.187 --> 01:25:13.101
Turn around.
You look like you've been born again.

1194
01:25:13.191 --> 01:25:15.432
Younger than the springtime.

1195
01:25:15.527 --> 01:25:19.191
I think that preacher laid hands
on you gave you a second life.

1196
01:25:19.281 --> 01:25:22.945
I knew it that moment I saw you,
you were special.

1197
01:25:23.035 --> 01:25:24.901
I tell you what, my knees are sore,

1198
01:25:24.995 --> 01:25:27.532
'cause I've been on them
every night asking the Lord,

1199
01:25:27.623 --> 01:25:31.366
I said,
"God, just bring him home safely."

1200
01:25:31.460 --> 01:25:33.952
Remember what I told you?

1201
01:25:34.046 --> 01:25:35.707
"You never know
what's coming for you?"

1202
01:25:35.797 --> 01:25:37.708
That's right. Sit down.

1203
01:25:39.092 --> 01:25:43.211
Well, you learn anything
worth repeating?

1204
01:25:45.307 --> 01:25:49.551
- I sure saw some things.
- Oh, you seen some pain.

1205
01:25:51.063 --> 01:25:53.805
- Some joy, too?
- Sure. Sure, I did.

1206
01:25:53.899 --> 01:25:58.063
Yeah, that's what I want to hear.
Look at you.

1207
01:25:58.153 --> 01:26:01.691
- Where's Tizzy?
- Oh, baby.

1208
01:26:04.117 --> 01:26:07.985
Mr. Weathers died in his
sleep one night last April.

1209
01:26:08.080 --> 01:26:11.573
- Mama, I'm so sorry.
- Don't you worry about that, baby.

1210
01:26:13.293 --> 01:26:15.955
Yeah, well, it's only
one or two of them left now.

1211
01:26:16.046 --> 01:26:17.502
They all just about new.

1212
01:26:17.589 --> 01:26:21.503
Guess they're waiting their
turn like everybody else, huh?

1213
01:26:21.593 --> 01:26:24.335
I'm so glad you're
back home with me!

1214
01:26:24.429 --> 01:26:27.592
Now, we're gonna have to find you
a wife and a new job! That's right.

1215
01:26:27.683 --> 01:26:29.594
Come on in here,
help me with this table.

1216
01:26:32.729 --> 01:26:34.345
Benjamin.

1217
01:26:34.439 --> 01:26:37.557
You're wasting your time, baby.
She's stone deaf.

1218
01:26:37.651 --> 01:26:41.690
Oh, and you'll be staying in
what was Mrs. DeSeroux's old room.

1219
01:26:41.780 --> 01:26:44.738
You're too big to be
rooming with anybody else.

1220
01:26:48.829 --> 01:26:51.446
<i>BENJAMIN: It's a funny thing
about coming home.</i>

1221
01:26:52.124 --> 01:26:55.913
<i>Looks the same,
smells the same, feels the same.</i>

1222
01:26:58.630 --> 01:27:02.464
Did I ever tell you I've been
struck by lightning seven times?

1223
01:27:04.136 --> 01:27:07.504
Once when I was sitting in my truck,
just minding my own business.

1224
01:27:09.933 --> 01:27:11.298
(EXHALING)

1225
01:27:13.353 --> 01:27:16.812
<i>BENJAMIN: You realize
what's changed is you.</i>

1226
01:27:19.484 --> 01:27:23.523
<i>And late one morning,
not long after I'd been back...</i>

1227
01:27:23.905 --> 01:27:25.270
Thank you.

1228
01:27:45.260 --> 01:27:46.842
(DOG BARKING)

1229
01:27:47.345 --> 01:27:48.426
Hey.

1230
01:27:51.433 --> 01:27:52.433
Oh.

1231
01:27:52.976 --> 01:27:56.844
- Excuse me, is Queenie here?
- Daisy?

1232
01:28:00.609 --> 01:28:04.227
- It's me, Benjamin.
- Benjamin?

1233
01:28:07.949 --> 01:28:09.940
Oh, my God!

1234
01:28:11.203 --> 01:28:15.162
Of course it's you! Benjamin!

1235
01:28:17.209 --> 01:28:20.122
How are you?
It's been such a long time.

1236
01:28:20.212 --> 01:28:22.954
There's so much I want to know.
When did you get back?

1237
01:28:23.048 --> 01:28:24.459
Well, I got back a few weeks ago.

1238
01:28:24.549 --> 01:28:28.543
I spoke to Queenie, she said you
were in the war, somewhere at sea.

1239
01:28:28.637 --> 01:28:32.380
- We were so, so worried about you.
- Oh, I'm okay.

1240
01:28:32.474 --> 01:28:36.388
Well, look at you. You're so lovely.

1241
01:28:38.146 --> 01:28:39.932
You stopped writing.

1242
01:28:42.025 --> 01:28:47.145
"When I had left, she was a girl.
And a woman had taken her place.

1243
01:28:47.447 --> 01:28:50.656
"She was the most beautiful
woman I'd ever seen."

1244
01:28:50.742 --> 01:28:52.073
Beautiful.

1245
01:28:54.246 --> 01:28:56.078
"The most beautiful."

1246
01:28:57.874 --> 01:28:59.685
- You remember Grandma Fuller?
- Why, sure I do.

1247
01:28:59.709 --> 01:29:02.792
- She passed.
- I heard that. I'm sorry.

1248
01:29:02.879 --> 01:29:07.498
I just can't believe we're both here.
Must be fate.

1249
01:29:07.592 --> 01:29:09.549
No, no, what do they call it?

1250
01:29:09.636 --> 01:29:11.047
Kismet.

1251
01:29:11.137 --> 01:29:13.048
Do you know about Edgar Cayce,
the psychic?

1252
01:29:13.139 --> 01:29:14.174
I don't believe I...

1253
01:29:14.266 --> 01:29:17.133
He says that everything
is predetermined,

1254
01:29:17.227 --> 01:29:20.595
but I like to think of it as fate.

1255
01:29:23.775 --> 01:29:27.018
I'm not sure how it works,
but I'm glad it happened.

1256
01:29:27.112 --> 01:29:30.730
Have you been to Manhattan?
It's right across the river from me.

1257
01:29:30.824 --> 01:29:32.986
Now, I can see the
Empire State Building

1258
01:29:33.076 --> 01:29:34.862
if I stand on my bed.

1259
01:29:34.953 --> 01:29:36.944
What about you?
Where have you been?

1260
01:29:37.038 --> 01:29:40.656
Tell me everything. Last time you wrote,
you said you'd been to Russia.

1261
01:29:40.750 --> 01:29:44.914
I've always wanted to go to Russia.
Is it as cold as they say?

1262
01:29:45.005 --> 01:29:47.793
- Twice as cold.
- My goodness.

1263
01:29:48.383 --> 01:29:53.093
We always said you were different.
But I think you really are.

1264
01:29:55.140 --> 01:29:58.724
You wrote that you met somebody.
Did it work out?

1265
01:29:59.185 --> 01:30:00.892
It ran its course.

1266
01:30:02.230 --> 01:30:04.312
Hey, do you remember this?

1267
01:30:15.160 --> 01:30:17.902
"This is the picture
of Old Man Kangaroo

1268
01:30:17.996 --> 01:30:20.112
"at 5:00 in the afternoon."

1269
01:30:21.917 --> 01:30:24.158
Would you like to have dinner?

1270
01:30:31.635 --> 01:30:34.548
<i>DAISY: Did I tell you that
I danced for Balanchine?</i>

1271
01:30:35.221 --> 01:30:39.761
<i>Oh, he's a famous choreographer.
He said that I had perfect line.</i>

1272
01:30:41.478 --> 01:30:46.018
<i>You know, in a rehearsal once,
a dancer fell.</i>

1273
01:30:46.107 --> 01:30:48.940
<i>And he just...
He just put it right into the production.</i>

1274
01:30:49.027 --> 01:30:52.520
<i>I mean, can you imagine that?
Like in a... in a classical ballet?</i>

1275
01:30:52.614 --> 01:30:55.857
<i>You know, a dancer,
intentionally falling.</i>

1276
01:30:55.951 --> 01:30:59.615
<i>There's a whole new word
for dance now. It's called "abstract."</i>

1277
01:30:59.704 --> 01:31:01.064
<i>No, he's not the only one, though.</i>

1278
01:31:01.122 --> 01:31:05.036
<i>There's Lincoln Kirstein
and Lucia Chase, and oh, my...</i>

1279
01:31:05.126 --> 01:31:07.618
<i>Oh, there's Agnes de Mille.</i>

1280
01:31:07.712 --> 01:31:09.794
<i>She's just torn up
all those conventions,</i>

1281
01:31:09.881 --> 01:31:11.872
<i>you know,
all that straight-up-and-down stuff.</i>

1282
01:31:11.967 --> 01:31:15.176
<i>It's not about the formality of the dance,
it's about what the dancer's feeling.</i>

1283
01:31:15.261 --> 01:31:17.969
<i>BENJAMIN: As she told me
about this big new world,</i>

1284
01:31:18.056 --> 01:31:20.593
<i>names that didn't mean a thing to me,</i>

1285
01:31:20.684 --> 01:31:22.804
<i>I didn't really hear very much
of what she was saying.</i>

1286
01:31:22.852 --> 01:31:25.093
<i>DAISY: It's new and it's modern
and it's American.</i>

1287
01:31:25.188 --> 01:31:28.351
They understand our
vigor and our physicality.

1288
01:31:28.441 --> 01:31:30.603
Oh, my God.
I've just been talking and talking.

1289
01:31:30.694 --> 01:31:35.188
No, no, I've enjoyed listening.
I didn't know you smoked.

1290
01:31:35.281 --> 01:31:36.863
I'm old enough.

1291
01:31:40.203 --> 01:31:42.740
I'm old enough for a lot of things.

1292
01:31:45.625 --> 01:31:48.083
In New York, we stay up all night,

1293
01:31:49.337 --> 01:31:52.170
watch the sun come up
over the warehouses.

1294
01:31:54.467 --> 01:31:56.799
There's always something to do.

1295
01:31:56.970 --> 01:32:00.133
(SOFT JAZZ MUSIC PLAYING)

1296
01:32:14.446 --> 01:32:16.608
I have to go back tomorrow.

1297
01:32:17.741 --> 01:32:19.903
- So soon.
- Wish I could stay.

1298
01:32:24.664 --> 01:32:27.873
Dancers don't need costumes
or scenery anymore.

1299
01:32:27.959 --> 01:32:31.497
I can imagine dancing
completely naked.

1300
01:32:32.797 --> 01:32:35.164
Have you read D. H. Lawrence?

1301
01:32:35.258 --> 01:32:37.374
- Well...
- His books were banned.

1302
01:32:37.469 --> 01:32:41.007
The words are like making love.

1303
01:33:25.517 --> 01:33:30.136
In our company,
we have to trust each other.

1304
01:33:35.401 --> 01:33:39.110
Sex is a part of it.

1305
01:33:43.493 --> 01:33:46.406
You know,
a lot of the dancers are lesbians.

1306
01:33:48.540 --> 01:33:51.658
There was one woman
who wanted to sleep with me.

1307
01:33:54.587 --> 01:33:56.624
(PEOPLE APPLAUDING)

1308
01:33:58.925 --> 01:34:01.963
- Does that upset you?
- Which part?

1309
01:34:03.054 --> 01:34:05.512
Somebody wanting to sleep with me.

1310
01:34:06.015 --> 01:34:07.176
You're a desirable woman.

1311
01:34:07.267 --> 01:34:11.010
I would think most of them
would want to sleep with you.

1312
01:34:11.104 --> 01:34:13.220
Let's go back to the house.

1313
01:34:14.149 --> 01:34:16.561
Or we could get a room somewhere.

1314
01:34:19.529 --> 01:34:22.738
- We could lay down your jacket.
- I don't know, Daisy.

1315
01:34:22.824 --> 01:34:28.194
It's not that I wouldn't like to or anything.
I think I'll just disappoint you.

1316
01:34:29.080 --> 01:34:32.198
Oh, Benjamin, I've been with older men.

1317
01:34:32.959 --> 01:34:34.996
You're going back to New York
in the morning.

1318
01:34:35.086 --> 01:34:37.418
You should be with your friends.

1319
01:34:38.423 --> 01:34:40.915
- You're only young once.
- Oh, I'm old enough.

1320
01:34:41.009 --> 01:34:43.626
(STERNLY) Daisy, just not tonight, is all.

1321
01:34:57.150 --> 01:34:59.312
We could go hear some music.

1322
01:35:01.571 --> 01:35:04.279
<i>BENJAMIN: Our lives are
defined by opportunities.</i>

1323
01:35:05.116 --> 01:35:07.107
<i>Even the ones we miss.</i>

1324
01:35:08.077 --> 01:35:11.615
You look so handsome
and so distinguished.

1325
01:35:11.706 --> 01:35:13.934
They're saying the hurricane's
gonna miss us, blow right on by.

1326
01:35:13.958 --> 01:35:18.577
- Oh, that's great.
- I'll stay under the blankets with Mother.

1327
01:35:18.671 --> 01:35:22.790
She says nothing... Benjamin?

1328
01:35:24.677 --> 01:35:25.821
"Things were becoming different..."

1329
01:35:25.845 --> 01:35:27.051
<i>BENJAMIN: ...for me.</i>

1330
01:35:27.138 --> 01:35:30.722
<i>My hair had very little gray
and grew like weeds.</i>

1331
01:35:30.808 --> 01:35:34.597
<i>My sense of smell was keener.
My hearing, more acute.</i>

1332
01:35:34.687 --> 01:35:37.349
<i>I could walk further and faster.</i>

1333
01:35:37.440 --> 01:35:43.231
<i>While everybody else was aging,
I was getting younger, all alone.</i>

1334
01:35:43.321 --> 01:35:44.607
(KNOCK ON DOOR)

1335
01:35:46.241 --> 01:35:47.481
Come in.

1336
01:35:48.868 --> 01:35:50.199
Benjamin.

1337
01:35:51.162 --> 01:35:54.405
- Do you remember me?
- Well, sure I do, Mr. Button.

1338
01:35:55.083 --> 01:35:58.667
- What happened to you?
- Darn foot. Got infected, so...

1339
01:36:00.338 --> 01:36:01.578
Welcome home, my friend.

1340
01:36:01.798 --> 01:36:03.209
(PEOPLE CHATTERING)

1341
01:36:04.259 --> 01:36:07.377
BENJAMIN: I see you're still drinking
your Sazerac with whiskey.

1342
01:36:07.470 --> 01:36:08.710
Creature of habit.

1343
01:36:08.805 --> 01:36:10.921
You still visiting the
house on Bourbon Street?

1344
01:36:11.015 --> 01:36:12.756
Not for a long time.

1345
01:36:14.352 --> 01:36:16.434
Interesting times, though.

1346
01:36:16.521 --> 01:36:20.981
We went from making 40,000
to nearly half a million buttons 3 day.

1347
01:36:21.067 --> 01:36:23.104
We employed 10 times
the number of people.

1348
01:36:23.194 --> 01:36:25.686
We were operating around the clock.

1349
01:36:30.243 --> 01:36:31.654
Damn shame.

1350
01:36:32.745 --> 01:36:35.703
The war has been kind
to the button industry.

1351
01:36:38.418 --> 01:36:39.783
You know,

1352
01:36:42.046 --> 01:36:45.380
I'm sick.
I don't know how much longer I have.

1353
01:36:45.466 --> 01:36:48.333
- I'm sorry to hear that, Mr. Button.
- No...

1354
01:36:49.721 --> 01:36:52.804
I don't have any people.
I keep to myself.

1355
01:36:55.268 --> 01:36:58.306
I hope you don't mind,
but, whenever possible,

1356
01:36:58.396 --> 01:37:00.387
I'd enjoy your company.

1357
01:37:00.481 --> 01:37:03.018
I'll certainly do what I can.

1358
01:37:06.279 --> 01:37:09.237
Benjamin, do you know
anything about buttons?

1359
01:37:12.785 --> 01:37:17.450
Now, Button's Buttons has been
in our family for 124 years.

1360
01:37:18.082 --> 01:37:22.701
My grandfather was a tailor,
and he had a small shop in Richmond.

1361
01:37:22.795 --> 01:37:25.207
After the Civil War,
he moved to New Orleans,

1362
01:37:25.298 --> 01:37:30.338
where my father had the wisdom
to make our own buttons.

1363
01:37:30.428 --> 01:37:35.343
So, with his help,
the tailor shop grew to this.

1364
01:37:36.059 --> 01:37:38.676
And today, I can't sew a stitch.

1365
01:37:42.857 --> 01:37:45.224
That's very, very interesting.

1366
01:37:48.654 --> 01:37:51.271
You sure have done well for yourself.

1367
01:37:52.200 --> 01:37:56.285
So, what can I do for you, Mr. Button?

1368
01:37:58.790 --> 01:38:01.828
Benjamin? You're my son.

1369
01:38:09.342 --> 01:38:12.004
I'm so sorry I never told you before.

1370
01:38:14.138 --> 01:38:17.551
You were born
the night the Great War ended.

1371
01:38:19.435 --> 01:38:23.144
Your mother died giving birth to you.

1372
01:38:24.649 --> 01:38:26.856
I thought you were a monster.

1373
01:38:30.405 --> 01:38:33.693
I promised your mother
I'd make sure you were safe.

1374
01:38:40.123 --> 01:38:42.581
I should never have abandoned you.

1375
01:38:46.671 --> 01:38:48.036
My mother?

1376
01:38:49.382 --> 01:38:52.340
THOMAS: At the summer
house on Lake Pontchartrain.

1377
01:38:52.427 --> 01:38:55.886
When I was a boy,
I'd love to wake up before anyone else,

1378
01:38:55.972 --> 01:38:59.010
run down to that lake
and watch the day begin.

1379
01:39:00.643 --> 01:39:03.305
It was as if I was the only one alive.

1380
01:39:05.106 --> 01:39:07.848
I fell in love the first time I saw her.

1381
01:39:08.359 --> 01:39:11.021
Your mother's name
was Caroline Murphy.

1382
01:39:11.654 --> 01:39:14.521
She worked in your
grandfather's kitchen.

1383
01:39:17.785 --> 01:39:19.492
She's from Dublin.

1384
01:39:20.121 --> 01:39:24.536
In 1903, Caroline and all her brothers
and sisters came to live here,

1385
01:39:24.625 --> 01:39:26.207
in New Orleans.

1386
01:39:28.296 --> 01:39:31.163
I'd find excuses
to go down to that kitchen

1387
01:39:31.966 --> 01:39:34.128
just so I could look at her.

1388
01:39:40.475 --> 01:39:44.218
April 25th, 1918.
Happiest day of my life.

1389
01:39:44.979 --> 01:39:47.220
The day I married your mother.

1390
01:39:48.941 --> 01:39:51.103
Why didn't you just tell me?

1391
01:39:51.944 --> 01:39:54.811
I plan on leaving
everything I have to you.

1392
01:39:56.324 --> 01:39:58.782
- I have to go.
- Where?

1393
01:39:59.827 --> 01:40:01.238
Home.

1394
01:40:01.913 --> 01:40:03.307
QUEENIE: And what does
he think, anyway?

1395
01:40:03.331 --> 01:40:04.662
He thinks he can just show up

1396
01:40:04.749 --> 01:40:06.615
and everything's supposed
to be fine and dandy.

1397
01:40:06.709 --> 01:40:09.326
Everybody's just supposed to be friends.

1398
01:40:09.420 --> 01:40:12.333
Well, he got another thing coming,
that's for sure.

1399
01:40:12.423 --> 01:40:15.836
God be my witness,
he got another thing coming.

1400
01:40:15.927 --> 01:40:19.010
He left us $18 that
night you was found.

1401
01:40:19.096 --> 01:40:20.928
Eighteen ratty dollars

1402
01:40:21.015 --> 01:40:22.756
- and a filthy diaper.
- Good night, Mama.

1403
01:40:24.101 --> 01:40:25.501
QUEENIE: (SOFTLY) Good night, baby.

1404
01:40:28.689 --> 01:40:30.805
(CLOCK CHIMING)

1405
01:40:38.574 --> 01:40:42.943
Did I ever tell you I was
struck by lightning seven times?

1406
01:40:44.705 --> 01:40:46.787
Once, I was walking
my dog down the road.

1407
01:40:51.754 --> 01:40:55.622
I'm blind in the one eye,
can't hardly hear,

1408
01:40:56.842 --> 01:41:01.461
get twitches and shakes out of nowhere,
always losing my line of thought.

1409
01:41:03.015 --> 01:41:04.722
But you know what?

1410
01:41:05.476 --> 01:41:08.434
God keeps reminding me
I'm lucky to be alive.

1411
01:41:11.899 --> 01:41:14.061
(SNIFFING)

1412
01:41:14.151 --> 01:41:15.733
Storm's coming.

1413
01:41:24.453 --> 01:41:26.035
(THUNDER RUMBLING)

1414
01:41:31.669 --> 01:41:33.080
(KNOCK ON DOOR)

1415
01:41:43.639 --> 01:41:45.880
May I help you, sir?
Up the stairs, first bedroom.

1416
01:41:45.975 --> 01:41:47.056
Thank you.

1417
01:42:02.908 --> 01:42:04.194
Wake up.

1418
01:42:06.704 --> 01:42:08.570
Let's get you dressed.

1419
01:42:35.983 --> 01:42:37.644
THOMAS: Now that's something.

1420
01:42:40.905 --> 01:42:42.270
Thank you.

1421
01:42:55.711 --> 01:42:57.418
(OWL HOOTING)

1422
01:43:42.425 --> 01:43:46.384
<i>BENJAMIN: You can be mad as
a mad dog at the way things went.</i>

1423
01:43:46.470 --> 01:43:48.928
<i>You can swear and curse the Fates.</i>

1424
01:43:50.474 --> 01:43:52.715
<i>But when it comes to the end,</i>

1425
01:43:53.936 --> 01:43:55.677
<i>you have to let go.</i>

1426
01:43:55.813 --> 01:43:57.929
(SIGHING CONTENTEDLY)

1427
01:44:01.819 --> 01:44:04.811
(CLOCK CHIMING)

1428
01:44:17.668 --> 01:44:20.285
QUEENIE: Well, it sure
is a beautiful service.

1429
01:44:22.131 --> 01:44:24.964
He'll be buried right
next to your mother.

1430
01:44:26.385 --> 01:44:28.046
You're my mother.

1431
01:44:30.097 --> 01:44:31.758
(QUEENIE CHUCKLING SOFTLY)

1432
01:44:31.849 --> 01:44:33.135
My baby.

1433
01:44:37.688 --> 01:44:39.850
<i>BENJAMIN: Now, I'd
never seen New York.</i>

1434
01:44:41.734 --> 01:44:43.475
(HORNS HONKING)

1435
01:46:01.689 --> 01:46:02.975
(AUDIENCE CHEERING)

1436
01:46:04.984 --> 01:46:06.941
(PEOPLE CHATTERING)

1437
01:46:08.028 --> 01:46:11.441
- Excuse me, I'm a friend of Daisy's.
- Right this way.

1438
01:46:12.449 --> 01:46:17.819
- Daisy has company. Daisy! Daisy!
- DAISY: Yes!

1439
01:46:18.205 --> 01:46:21.493
- WOMAN: We need the wardrobe.
- Is somebody looking for me?

1440
01:46:24.086 --> 01:46:26.293
- Benjamin.
- Hi.

1441
01:46:27.590 --> 01:46:31.379
- What are you doing here?
- Thought I'd come visit.

1442
01:46:31.468 --> 01:46:34.927
Spend some time with you, if I could.

1443
01:46:35.014 --> 01:46:40.930
Oh, well, I wish you would've called.
You took me by surprise.

1444
01:46:42.271 --> 01:46:46.435
- You can just throw them out.
- No. Thank you, they're lovely.

1445
01:46:47.026 --> 01:46:51.862
I couldn't take my eyes off of you.
I thought you were mesmerizing.

1446
01:46:53.866 --> 01:46:56.699
Thank you.
That's very kind of you to say.

1447
01:47:01.999 --> 01:47:04.144
I better get changed.
A group of us are going to a party.

1448
01:47:04.168 --> 01:47:07.411
- Would you want to come?
- Someone told me about a restaurant

1449
01:47:07.504 --> 01:47:08.790
I thought you might enjoy.

1450
01:47:08.881 --> 01:47:11.418
I made a reservation, just in case.

1451
01:47:11.508 --> 01:47:14.500
Just, all the dancers go
out after the show. You're...

1452
01:47:14.595 --> 01:47:18.429
You're welcome to come with us.
I'll get changed. All right?

1453
01:47:24.855 --> 01:47:26.971
She choreographs
for the Ballets Russes.

1454
01:47:27.066 --> 01:47:28.397
She's divine.

1455
01:47:29.026 --> 01:47:30.858
You were breathtaking.

1456
01:47:30.986 --> 01:47:32.943
(MUSIC PLAYING LOUDLY)

1457
01:47:33.030 --> 01:47:34.646
(PEOPLE CHATTERING)

1458
01:47:36.533 --> 01:47:37.819
Sweetie.

1459
01:47:38.953 --> 01:47:41.866
This is David.
He dances with the company.

1460
01:47:42.831 --> 01:47:44.868
- This is Benjamin.
- Who?

1461
01:47:44.959 --> 01:47:48.202
- I told you about him.
- Oh, yeah. How you doing?

1462
01:47:48.295 --> 01:47:51.788
- I'll go get you a drink.
- All right. Thanks.

1463
01:47:59.473 --> 01:48:02.636
So, you were a friend
of her grandmother's?

1464
01:48:02.726 --> 01:48:04.683
Or something like that?

1465
01:48:05.813 --> 01:48:07.599
Something like that.

1466
01:48:07.898 --> 01:48:09.480
Hey, excuse me.

1467
01:48:11.318 --> 01:48:13.184
(CHATTERING)

1468
01:48:18.575 --> 01:48:19.575
(DAISY LAUGHING)

1469
01:48:31.797 --> 01:48:33.083
Come on.

1470
01:48:54.403 --> 01:48:55.484
DAISY: Hey!

1471
01:48:56.447 --> 01:48:58.939
Now, I had no idea you were coming.

1472
01:48:59.950 --> 01:49:01.532
Lord, Benjamin.

1473
01:49:04.121 --> 01:49:07.989
What did you expect?
What, you want me to drop everything?

1474
01:49:08.083 --> 01:49:10.040
Now, this is my life.

1475
01:49:10.127 --> 01:49:12.619
Babe! You going downtown?

1476
01:49:17.551 --> 01:49:20.669
Come on. You'll have a good time.

1477
01:49:21.513 --> 01:49:23.116
There's lots of musicians,
interesting people.

1478
01:49:23.140 --> 01:49:26.053
You don't have to do that.
This is my fault.

1479
01:49:27.144 --> 01:49:28.555
I should've called.

1480
01:49:28.645 --> 01:49:31.478
I thought I'd come here

1481
01:49:31.565 --> 01:49:34.307
and sweep you off your feet
or something.

1482
01:49:35.819 --> 01:49:40.313
- Daisy! Come on! Let's go.
- Be right there.

1483
01:49:42.076 --> 01:49:43.487
BENJAMIN: Seems nice.

1484
01:49:44.828 --> 01:49:46.444
Do you love him?

1485
01:49:49.541 --> 01:49:50.952
I think so.

1486
01:49:53.045 --> 01:49:54.752
I'm happy for you.

1487
01:49:56.673 --> 01:49:58.789
Maybe I'll see you at home.

1488
01:50:01.386 --> 01:50:02.501
Okay.

1489
01:50:04.515 --> 01:50:06.301
I enjoyed the show!

1490
01:50:13.899 --> 01:50:18.439
He came to tell me
his father had died.

1491
01:50:19.905 --> 01:50:26.117
- You couldn't have known.
- I was 23. I... I just didn't care.

1492
01:50:26.995 --> 01:50:28.577
(THUNDER RUMBLING)

1493
01:50:28.664 --> 01:50:30.029
What did you do next?

1494
01:50:30.124 --> 01:50:37.087
Some photographs, I think,
in the front of my bag.

1495
01:50:39.174 --> 01:50:43.293
I was as good a dancer
as I was ever gonna be.

1496
01:50:45.180 --> 01:50:47.137
For five years, I...

1497
01:50:49.893 --> 01:50:51.679
I danced everywhere.

1498
01:50:53.105 --> 01:50:56.643
London, Vienna, Prague.

1499
01:50:57.234 --> 01:50:59.100
I've never seen these.

1500
01:51:02.406 --> 01:51:03.521
Mom.

1501
01:51:04.783 --> 01:51:07.491
You never talked about your dancing.

1502
01:51:07.578 --> 01:51:09.615
Well, I was the only American

1503
01:51:09.705 --> 01:51:14.666
to be invited to dance
with the Bolshoi, sugar.

1504
01:51:16.503 --> 01:51:18.540
<i>DAISY: It was glorious.</i>

1505
01:51:18.881 --> 01:51:20.246
(BELL RINGING)

1506
01:51:22.968 --> 01:51:26.711
<i>But Benjamin was never
far from my thoughts.</i>

1507
01:51:29.850 --> 01:51:33.434
<i>And I'd find myself saying...</i>

1508
01:51:33.520 --> 01:51:35.352
Good night, Benjamin.

1509
01:51:37.316 --> 01:51:40.980
- "Good night, Daisy."
- He said that?

1510
01:51:43.113 --> 01:51:44.473
"Life wasn't all that complicated.

1511
01:51:45.157 --> 01:51:47.945
<i>"If you want, you might say
I was looking for something."</i>

1512
01:51:57.419 --> 01:52:00.411
Benjamin?
Mrs. La Tourneau just passed.

1513
01:52:06.803 --> 01:52:10.467
- Letter for Mr. Benjamin Button?
- That'd be me.

1514
01:52:13.352 --> 01:52:14.717
Thank you.

1515
01:52:38.752 --> 01:52:40.914
(BOTH SPEAKING FRENCH)

1516
01:52:41.004 --> 01:52:42.915
Miss Daisy Fuller.

1517
01:52:43.006 --> 01:52:45.839
- Just a minute. Please have a seat.
- Sure.

1518
01:52:50.180 --> 01:52:53.218
(NURSE SPEAKING FRENCH)

1519
01:52:53.308 --> 01:52:55.720
<i>BENJAMIN: Sometimes
we're on a collision course</i>

1520
01:52:55.811 --> 01:52:57.722
<i>and we just don't know it.</i>

1521
01:52:58.272 --> 01:53:02.812
<i>Whether it's by accident or by design,
there's not a thing we can do about it.</i>

1522
01:53:05.612 --> 01:53:08.695
<i>A woman in Paris was on
her way to go shopping.</i>

1523
01:53:10.033 --> 01:53:13.776
<i>But she had forgotten her coat,
went back to get it.</i>

1524
01:53:13.870 --> 01:53:16.077
<i>When she had gotten her coat,
the phone had rung.</i>

1525
01:53:16.164 --> 01:53:19.202
<i>So she had stopped to answer it
and talked for a couple of minutes.</i>

1526
01:53:20.669 --> 01:53:22.455
<i>While the woman was on the phone,</i>

1527
01:53:22.546 --> 01:53:26.756
<i>Daisy was rehearsing for a performance
at the Paris Opera House.</i>

1528
01:53:26.842 --> 01:53:29.630
<i>And while she was rehearsing,
the woman, off the phone now,</i>

1529
01:53:29.720 --> 01:53:32.052
<i>had gone outside to get a taxi.</i>

1530
01:53:36.560 --> 01:53:38.847
<i>Now, a taxi driver had
dropped off a fare earlier,</i>

1531
01:53:38.937 --> 01:53:41.679
<i>and had stopped to
get a cup of coffee.</i>

1532
01:53:42.566 --> 01:53:45.308
<i>And all the while,
Daisy was rehearsing.</i>

1533
01:53:48.822 --> 01:53:51.314
<i>And this cab driver,
who dropped off the earlier fare</i>

1534
01:53:51.408 --> 01:53:53.399
<i>and had stopped to
get the cup of coffee,</i>

1535
01:53:53.493 --> 01:53:55.213
<i>he picked up the lady
who was going shopping</i>

1536
01:53:55.287 --> 01:53:57.403
<i>and had missed getting the earlier cab.</i>

1537
01:53:57.497 --> 01:53:58.862
(TIRES SCREECHING)

1538
01:53:58.957 --> 01:54:01.369
<i>The taxi had to stop
for a man crossing the street,</i>

1539
01:54:01.460 --> 01:54:04.293
<i>who had left for work five minutes
later than he normally did</i>

1540
01:54:04.379 --> 01:54:06.916
<i>because he forgot to set his alarm.</i>

1541
01:54:07.674 --> 01:54:10.962
<i>While that man, late for work,
was crossing the street,</i>

1542
01:54:11.053 --> 01:54:14.512
<i>Daisy had finished rehearsing
and was taking a shower.</i>

1543
01:54:15.015 --> 01:54:16.346
<i>And while Daisy was showering,</i>

1544
01:54:16.433 --> 01:54:20.051
<i>the taxi was waiting outside a boutique
for the woman to pick up a package</i>

1545
01:54:20.145 --> 01:54:21.331
<i>which hadn't been wrapped yet,</i>

1546
01:54:21.355 --> 01:54:23.187
<i>because the girl who
was supposed to wrap it</i>

1547
01:54:23.273 --> 01:54:26.891
<i>had broken up with her boyfriend
the night before and forgot.</i>

1548
01:54:27.527 --> 01:54:30.736
<i>When the package was wrapped,
the woman, who was back in the cab,</i>

1549
01:54:30.822 --> 01:54:32.483
<i>was blocked by a delivery truck.</i>

1550
01:54:32.574 --> 01:54:35.316
<i>All the while,
Daisy was getting dressed.</i>

1551
01:54:36.787 --> 01:54:40.200
<i>The delivery truck pulled away,
and the taxi was able to move</i>

1552
01:54:40.290 --> 01:54:42.372
<i>while Daisy, the last to be dressed,</i>

1553
01:54:42.459 --> 01:54:46.043
<i>waited for one of her friends
who had broken a shoelace.</i>

1554
01:54:46.463 --> 01:54:49.376
<i>While the taxi was stopped,
waiting for a traffic light,</i>

1555
01:54:49.466 --> 01:54:53.380
<i>Daisy and her friend came
out the back of the theater.</i>

1556
01:54:53.470 --> 01:54:56.883
<i>And if only one thing
had happened differently,</i>

1557
01:54:56.973 --> 01:54:59.055
<i>if that shoelace hadn't broken</i>

1558
01:54:59.142 --> 01:55:01.679
<i>or that delivery truck had
moved moments earlier</i>

1559
01:55:01.770 --> 01:55:03.636
<i>or that package had been
wrapped and ready</i>

1560
01:55:03.730 --> 01:55:06.472
<i>because the girl hadn't
broken up with her boyfriend,</i>

1561
01:55:06.566 --> 01:55:10.230
<i>or that man had set his alarm
and got up five minutes earlier</i>

1562
01:55:10.320 --> 01:55:13.529
<i>or that taxi driver hadn't
stopped for a cup of coffee</i>

1563
01:55:13.615 --> 01:55:17.654
<i>or that woman had remembered
her coat and got into an earlier cab,</i>

1564
01:55:18.161 --> 01:55:20.869
<i>Daisy and her friend would
have crossed the street</i>

1565
01:55:20.956 --> 01:55:23.323
<i>and the taxi would have driven by.</i>

1566
01:55:23.417 --> 01:55:25.033
(NURSE SPEAKING FRENCH)

1567
01:55:34.469 --> 01:55:36.210
<i>But, life being what it is,</i>

1568
01:55:36.304 --> 01:55:39.296
<i>a series of intersecting
lives and incidents</i>

1569
01:55:39.391 --> 01:55:41.177
<i>out of anyone's control,</i>

1570
01:55:42.018 --> 01:55:44.760
<i>that taxi did not go by,</i>

1571
01:55:44.855 --> 01:55:47.688
<i>and that driver was
momentarily distracted.</i>

1572
01:55:48.692 --> 01:55:49.773
<i>WOMAN: (SHOUTING) Daisy!</i>

1573
01:55:49.860 --> 01:55:51.170
<i>BENJAMIN: And that taxi hit Daisy.</i>

1574
01:55:51.194 --> 01:55:52.935
WOMAN: Daisy! Help!

1575
01:55:56.074 --> 01:55:58.065
<i>BENJAMIN: And her leg was crushed.</i>

1576
01:56:05.459 --> 01:56:06.665
Daisy?

1577
01:56:10.922 --> 01:56:13.505
- Who told you?
- Your friend wired me.

1578
01:56:14.551 --> 01:56:18.636
Very kind of you to come all this
way to see that I was all right.

1579
01:56:20.182 --> 01:56:22.219
You'd do the same for me.

1580
01:56:24.102 --> 01:56:25.342
My God.

1581
01:56:27.439 --> 01:56:30.932
Look at you. You're perfect.

1582
01:56:33.737 --> 01:56:38.277
I wish you hadn't come here.
I don't want you to see me like this.

1583
01:56:40.118 --> 01:56:42.655
(NURSE SPEAKING FRENCH)

1584
01:56:44.706 --> 01:56:46.993
<i>BENJAMIN: Her leg had
been broken in five places.</i>

1585
01:56:47.083 --> 01:56:50.246
<i>And with therapy and time,
she might walk again.</i>

1586
01:56:51.755 --> 01:56:53.666
<i>But she'd never dance.</i>

1587
01:56:55.258 --> 01:56:57.716
I'm gonna take you home with me.

1588
01:56:57.802 --> 01:57:00.590
- I want to look after you.
- I'm not going back to New Orleans.

1589
01:57:00.680 --> 01:57:02.887
Then I'll stay here in Paris.

1590
01:57:03.475 --> 01:57:06.433
Don't you understand?
I don't want your help.

1591
01:57:07.521 --> 01:57:11.856
I know I'm feeling sorry for myself,
but I don't want to be with you.

1592
01:57:11.942 --> 01:57:15.731
Tried to tell you that in New York.
You don't listen.

1593
01:57:17.239 --> 01:57:19.196
You might change your mind.

1594
01:57:19.282 --> 01:57:22.274
We are not little children
anymore, Benjamin.

1595
01:57:24.287 --> 01:57:27.530
Just stay out of my life.

1596
01:57:37.634 --> 01:57:39.375
(CHAIR CREAKING)

1597
01:57:50.355 --> 01:57:53.643
<i>DAISY: I was awfully cruel.</i>

1598
01:57:54.693 --> 01:58:00.154
He didn't understand.
I couldn't have him see me like that.

1599
01:58:02.826 --> 01:58:04.191
"I didn't leave right away.

1600
01:58:06.830 --> 01:58:10.164
<i>"I stayed in Paris for a
while to look out for her."</i>

1601
01:58:13.712 --> 01:58:15.578
I never knew that.

1602
01:58:18.967 --> 01:58:23.052
Oh, darling, could you get the nurse?

1603
01:58:26.725 --> 01:58:31.845
I taught myself to walk again.

1604
01:58:34.899 --> 01:58:37.482
I took the train to Lourdes.

1605
01:58:38.820 --> 01:58:44.406
Let's take a look. That's normal.
Pulse rate is slowing.

1606
01:58:44.492 --> 01:58:46.483
She is gonna struggle to breathe.

1607
01:58:46.578 --> 01:58:48.819
- Will you be all right?
- Yeah.

1608
01:59:01.968 --> 01:59:07.884
All right, he says, "I went back home."
And then there's a lot of pages torn out.

1609
01:59:08.099 --> 01:59:11.842
"I listened to the sound of the house."
I read that already.

1610
01:59:12.729 --> 01:59:13.844
He...

1611
01:59:14.773 --> 01:59:18.061
He spilt something on it,
so it's hard to read, Mom.

1612
01:59:19.194 --> 01:59:21.982
Something about sailing,
does that make sense?

1613
01:59:22.697 --> 01:59:26.065
<i>BENJAMIN: I learned to sail an old boat
of my father's from the lake house.</i>

1614
01:59:28.203 --> 01:59:31.321
<i>(MY PRAYER</i> PLAYING)

1615
01:59:35.251 --> 01:59:37.242
<i>I can't lie.</i>

1616
01:59:37.337 --> 01:59:40.170
<i>I did enjoy the company
of a woman or two.</i>

1617
01:59:48.473 --> 01:59:50.055
<i>Or maybe three.</i>

1618
01:59:52.769 --> 01:59:54.430
(ELECTRIC RAZOR HUMMING)

1619
02:00:26.553 --> 02:00:30.797
Don't know why you bother, Sam,
just gonna be there again tomorrow.

1620
02:00:35.145 --> 02:00:36.306
Mama.

1621
02:00:41.151 --> 02:00:43.643
<i>BENJAMIN: And in the spring of 1962,</i>

1622
02:00:47.490 --> 02:00:49.026
<i>she came back.</i>

1623
02:01:08.386 --> 02:01:12.050
- You want to know where I've been?
- No.

1624
02:01:14.017 --> 02:01:18.932
How come you didn't write or nothing?
Just disappearing like that.

1625
02:01:19.022 --> 02:01:21.605
It was something I needed
to do for myself.

1626
02:01:21.691 --> 02:01:25.434
Yeah, well, I never took you
to be the selfish type.

1627
02:01:25.528 --> 02:01:28.020
I sure hope I'm not wrong.

1628
02:01:29.157 --> 02:01:31.239
I'm usually not wrong about people.

1629
02:01:31.326 --> 02:01:33.863
- Good night, Mama.
- Good night, baby.

1630
02:01:34.829 --> 02:01:36.490
Y'all have fun.

1631
02:01:39.209 --> 02:01:43.578
- You haven't said two words.
- I don't want to ruin it.

1632
02:02:01.022 --> 02:02:03.229
(CLOCK TICKING)

1633
02:02:06.444 --> 02:02:07.900
(DOOR CLOSING)

1634
02:02:13.743 --> 02:02:16.075
- Sleep with me?
- Absolutely.

1635
02:02:48.361 --> 02:02:50.693
(TICKING)

1636
02:02:53.825 --> 02:02:56.283
<i>BENJAMIN: I asked her
to come away with me.</i>

1637
02:02:58.496 --> 02:03:01.614
<i>We sailed into the Gulf
along the Florida Keys.</i>

1638
02:03:13.928 --> 02:03:15.384
(DAISY LAUGHING)

1639
02:03:42.957 --> 02:03:47.326
DAISY: I am so glad we didn't
find one another when I was 26.

1640
02:03:47.420 --> 02:03:51.755
BENJAMIN: Why do you say that?
DAISY: I was so young.

1641
02:03:51.841 --> 02:03:53.627
And you were so old.

1642
02:03:54.302 --> 02:03:57.215
It happened when it
was supposed to happen.

1643
02:03:57.305 --> 02:04:00.423
BENJAMIN: I will enjoy each and
every moment I have with you.

1644
02:04:00.516 --> 02:04:01.847
(THUNDER CRASHING)

1645
02:04:05.605 --> 02:04:08.097
DAISY: I bet I can stay
out here longer than you.

1646
02:04:08.191 --> 02:04:09.807
BENJAMIN: I bet you can't.

1647
02:04:12.654 --> 02:04:15.191
DAISY: Barely a line or a crease.

1648
02:04:15.573 --> 02:04:18.736
Every day I have more wrinkles.
It's not fair.

1649
02:04:20.370 --> 02:04:24.159
BENJAMIN: I love your wrinkles.
Both of them.

1650
02:04:29.837 --> 02:04:32.169
What's it like growing younger?

1651
02:04:34.592 --> 02:04:39.211
I can't really say.
I'm always looking out my own eyes.

1652
02:04:44.227 --> 02:04:48.016
DAISY: Will you still love me
when my skin grows old and saggy?

1653
02:04:48.106 --> 02:04:52.600
Will you still love me when I have acne?
When I wet the bed?

1654
02:04:53.903 --> 02:04:56.770
When I'm afraid of
what's under the stairs?

1655
02:05:04.247 --> 02:05:05.328
What?

1656
02:05:11.337 --> 02:05:15.331
- What are you thinking?
- Well, I was thinking how nothing lasts.

1657
02:05:17.719 --> 02:05:19.756
And what a shame that is.

1658
02:05:22.724 --> 02:05:24.385
Some things last.

1659
02:05:26.644 --> 02:05:30.888
- Good night, Daisy.
- Good night, Benjamin.

1660
02:05:47.290 --> 02:05:48.371
Mom?

1661
02:05:48.458 --> 02:05:49.458
DAISY: Mmm-hmm?

1662
02:05:50.626 --> 02:05:54.665
- When did you meet Dad?
<i>- Some</i> time after that.

1663
02:05:57.800 --> 02:06:02.545
- Did you tell him about this Benjamin?
- He knew enough, darling.

1664
02:06:22.533 --> 02:06:23.648
Mama?

1665
02:06:30.833 --> 02:06:32.119
Queenie?

1666
02:06:35.254 --> 02:06:36.585
Hello?

1667
02:06:37.006 --> 02:06:40.624
Oh, hi, Mrs. Carter, it's Benjamin.
Where is everybody?

1668
02:06:40.718 --> 02:06:45.929
Oh, Benjamin. Queenie died.
I'm so sorry.

1669
02:06:48.476 --> 02:06:50.183
(CHOIR SINGING <i>I'll FLYAWAY)</i>

1670
02:07:14.585 --> 02:07:17.998
MAN: I'm so sorry for your loss.
She was a great woman.

1671
02:07:18.089 --> 02:07:19.921
Our deepest condolences.

1672
02:07:25.054 --> 02:07:28.092
<i>BENJAMIN: We buried her
beside her beloved Mr. Weathers.</i>

1673
02:07:35.064 --> 02:07:38.557
<i>And so we might have
memories of our own,</i>

1674
02:07:38.651 --> 02:07:40.608
<i>we sold my father's
house on Esplanade.</i>

1675
02:07:40.695 --> 02:07:43.312
It is a wonderful old place, darling.

1676
02:07:43.906 --> 02:07:46.819
I think we are going
to be so happy here.

1677
02:07:46.909 --> 02:07:49.822
Oh, what a long family
history you have.

1678
02:07:49.912 --> 02:07:51.903
They come with the house.

1679
02:07:54.500 --> 02:07:55.661
Come on.

1680
02:07:55.751 --> 02:07:57.458
WOMAN: You have to
see the master suite.

1681
02:07:58.921 --> 02:08:01.162
<i>BENJAMIN: We bought
ourselves a duplex.</i>

1682
02:08:03.217 --> 02:08:05.254
DAISY: I loved that house.

1683
02:08:07.680 --> 02:08:09.671
It smelled like firewood.

1684
02:08:10.766 --> 02:08:14.009
Don't... Don't stop, darling.

1685
02:08:14.604 --> 02:08:17.471
"It was one of the
happiest times of my life."

1686
02:08:17.565 --> 02:08:20.102
<i>BENJAMIN: We didn't have
a stick of furniture.</i>

1687
02:08:20.902 --> 02:08:23.644
<i>We would have picnics
in the living room.</i>

1688
02:08:25.156 --> 02:08:27.022
<i>(TWIST AND SHOUT</i> PLAYING)

1689
02:08:27.116 --> 02:08:31.110
<i>We ate when we felt like it.
Stayed up all night when we wanted.</i>

1690
02:08:32.538 --> 02:08:34.529
<i>We vowed never to fall into routine,</i>

1691
02:08:34.624 --> 02:08:37.491
<i>to go to bed or wake up
at the same time.</i>

1692
02:08:37.585 --> 02:08:39.622
<i>We lived on that mattress.</i>

1693
02:09:15.331 --> 02:09:18.824
<i>Our neighbor, a Mrs. Van Dam,
was a physical therapist.</i>

1694
02:09:20.419 --> 02:09:23.161
<i>We lived four blocks
from a public pool.</i>

1695
02:09:27.093 --> 02:09:29.835
(PANTING)

1696
02:09:45.111 --> 02:09:46.897
(SOBBING)

1697
02:10:01.544 --> 02:10:04.332
You know, you might've got
a few more years out of it,

1698
02:10:04.422 --> 02:10:08.541
but you chose to do something
so special and unique

1699
02:10:09.969 --> 02:10:13.712
that there was only a short
window of time you could do it.

1700
02:10:15.516 --> 02:10:18.008
So, even if nothing ever happened,

1701
02:10:18.102 --> 02:10:21.220
you'd still be right here
where you are now.

1702
02:10:21.314 --> 02:10:23.555
I just don't like getting old.

1703
02:10:25.109 --> 02:10:27.646
They put too much chlorine in here.

1704
02:11:08.903 --> 02:11:12.771
I promise you I'll never lose
myself to self-pity again.

1705
02:11:17.119 --> 02:11:20.202
<i>BENJAMIN: And
I think right there and then</i>

1706
02:11:20.289 --> 02:11:24.283
<i>she realized none of us
is perfect forever.</i>

1707
02:11:28.255 --> 02:11:29.871
<i>She found peace.</i>

1708
02:11:31.759 --> 02:11:34.672
<i>She opened a studio and
taught young girls how to dance.</i>

1709
02:11:34.762 --> 02:11:37.880
<i>And tend...</i>

1710
02:11:37.973 --> 02:11:43.059
Come back the other way.
And spot, spot, spot. Excellent.

1711
02:11:43.145 --> 02:11:44.635
(GIRLS CHATTERING)

1712
02:11:44.730 --> 02:11:47.188
- Good night, Miss Daisy.
- Good night.

1713
02:12:09.839 --> 02:12:10.954
(EXCLAIMING)

1714
02:12:12.675 --> 02:12:15.292
You certainly are beautiful to watch.

1715
02:12:17.096 --> 02:12:19.508
Dancing's all about the line.

1716
02:12:21.767 --> 02:12:23.678
The line of your body.

1717
02:12:25.020 --> 02:12:29.355
Sooner or later, you lose that line,
and you never get it back.

1718
02:12:35.239 --> 02:12:41.201
I figure, you were born in 1918,
49 years ago.

1719
02:12:41.287 --> 02:12:42.823
I'm 43.

1720
02:12:44.999 --> 02:12:47.536
We are almost the same age.

1721
02:12:50.838 --> 02:12:55.048
- We're meeting in the middle.
- We finally caught up with each other.

1722
02:12:56.218 --> 02:12:57.333
Wait.

1723
02:12:58.679 --> 02:13:01.341
I want to remember us
just as we are now.

1724
02:13:12.193 --> 02:13:13.683
I'm pregnant.

1725
02:13:31.378 --> 02:13:35.042
You know, I swear the nurse slipped
and said it was a boy.

1726
02:13:50.022 --> 02:13:52.013
But I think it's a girl.

1727
02:13:57.321 --> 02:14:00.905
- I know you're afraid.
- I'm not hiding it.

1728
02:14:00.991 --> 02:14:02.106
Okay.

1729
02:14:09.458 --> 02:14:12.041
- What's your worst fear?
- Baby born like me.

1730
02:14:12.127 --> 02:14:14.585
Then I will love it all the more.

1731
02:14:16.590 --> 02:14:21.551
Okay. How can I be a father
when I'm heading in the other direction?

1732
02:14:22.179 --> 02:14:25.513
It's not fair to a child.
I don't want to be anybody's burden.

1733
02:14:25.599 --> 02:14:28.466
Sugar, we all end up in diapers.

1734
02:14:29.937 --> 02:14:31.974
I am gonna make this work.

1735
02:14:34.650 --> 02:14:37.563
I want this, and I want it with you.

1736
02:14:37.653 --> 02:14:41.066
I want you to have everything
you want, all of it.

1737
02:14:41.156 --> 02:14:44.365
I'm just not sure
how to reconcile this.

1738
02:14:44.451 --> 02:14:46.533
Would you tell a blind man
he couldn't have children?

1739
02:14:46.620 --> 02:14:48.202
Here you go.

1740
02:14:48.289 --> 02:14:51.748
You'll be a father for
as long as you can.

1741
02:14:51.834 --> 02:14:54.622
I know the consequences.
I've accepted that.

1742
02:14:54.712 --> 02:14:57.329
Loving you is worth everything to me.

1743
02:15:01.844 --> 02:15:03.505
I have to go pee.

1744
02:15:17.568 --> 02:15:19.879
<i>MAN ON TV: The oldest woman
to ever swim the English Channel</i>

1745
02:15:19.903 --> 02:15:21.644
<i>arrived here today in Calais...</i>

1746
02:15:21.739 --> 02:15:24.231
- Keep it.
- <i>...having made the swim in 34 hours,</i>

1747
02:15:24.325 --> 02:15:26.532
<i>22 minutes and 14 seconds.</i>

1748
02:15:26.619 --> 02:15:31.455
<i>The 68-year-old Elizabeth Abbott
arrived at 5:38 Greenwich mean time,</i>

1749
02:15:31.540 --> 02:15:33.326
<i>exhausted but happy.</i>

1750
02:15:33.417 --> 02:15:36.955
<i>Miss Abbott, how would you sum up,
in words, this achievement?</i>

1751
02:15:37.046 --> 02:15:38.536
<i>I suppose...</i>

1752
02:15:38.922 --> 02:15:39.922
<i>(PANTING)</i>

1753
02:15:40.049 --> 02:15:41.790
<i>Anything's possible.</i>

1754
02:15:41.884 --> 02:15:43.466
<i>(LAUGHING)</i>

1755
02:15:45.804 --> 02:15:47.032
<i>ELIZABETH: All right?
MAN: Yes. Thank you.</i>

1756
02:15:47.056 --> 02:15:48.116
- You ready?
<i>- MAN: Thank you very much.</i>

1757
02:15:48.140 --> 02:15:50.097
<i>ELIZABETH: Thank you. Thank you all.</i>

1758
02:15:50.184 --> 02:15:52.175
<i>- Yeah.
- You're very kind.</i>

1759
02:15:59.401 --> 02:16:03.269
<i>BENJAMIN: In the spring,
on a day like any other...</i>

1760
02:16:04.031 --> 02:16:06.022
I'll be back in an hour!

1761
02:16:06.533 --> 02:16:07.568
(DAISY SCREAMS)

1762
02:16:07.660 --> 02:16:08.660
(THUDDING)

1763
02:16:11.038 --> 02:16:12.244
Honey?

1764
02:16:14.291 --> 02:16:16.328
Go and call an ambulance!

1765
02:16:19.254 --> 02:16:20.915
The baby's coming.

1766
02:16:21.757 --> 02:16:22.859
Operator, I need an ambulance.

1767
02:16:22.883 --> 02:16:25.341
- The baby's coming!
- BENJAMIN: 2714 Napoleon.

1768
02:16:25.427 --> 02:16:26.633
(GASPING)

1769
02:16:27.971 --> 02:16:29.461
(DAISY GROANING)

1770
02:16:32.559 --> 02:16:35.267
WOMAN: There you go. Keep breathing.

1771
02:16:36.146 --> 02:16:38.513
Deep breaths. Push.

1772
02:16:38.607 --> 02:16:40.189
(DAISY GROANING)

1773
02:16:48.450 --> 02:16:49.861
WOMAN: There we go.

1774
02:16:54.248 --> 02:16:56.285
(DAISY GROANING)

1775
02:16:57.459 --> 02:16:59.291
(BABY CRYING)

1776
02:17:06.260 --> 02:17:09.628
Everyone's fine.
She's a perfectly healthy baby girl.

1777
02:17:16.520 --> 02:17:17.726
Honey?

1778
02:17:19.648 --> 02:17:23.312
<i>BENJAMIN: She gave birth to a
five pound, four ounce baby girl.</i>

1779
02:17:39.501 --> 02:17:41.412
Did you count the toes?

1780
02:17:45.716 --> 02:17:47.252
She's perfect.

1781
02:17:47.676 --> 02:17:50.964
"And we named her
for my mother, Caroline."

1782
02:17:54.683 --> 02:17:56.845
This Benjamin was my father?

1783
02:17:58.353 --> 02:18:00.515
And this is how you tell me?

1784
02:18:06.069 --> 02:18:07.434
Excuse me.

1785
02:18:17.915 --> 02:18:20.657
<i>...because all the ingredients
are there for a major storm,</i>

1786
02:18:20.751 --> 02:18:23.334
<i>possibly even up to a Category 5.</i>

1787
02:18:30.052 --> 02:18:33.761
Hey, I know it's hard.
You can't smoke in here.

1788
02:18:37.100 --> 02:18:39.020
<i>Nobody can tell you exactly
where it's gonna hit,</i>

1789
02:18:39.061 --> 02:18:41.223
<i>but we have to go with the
guidance that we have,</i>

1790
02:18:41.313 --> 02:18:45.056
<i>incorporate that information
and then pass it along to you.</i>

1791
02:18:51.907 --> 02:18:56.743
"You grew as the doctor had promised,
normal and healthy."

1792
02:19:05.420 --> 02:19:08.538
You're gonna have to
find a real father for her.

1793
02:19:08.632 --> 02:19:10.418
(PEOPLE CHATTERING)

1794
02:19:11.677 --> 02:19:13.463
What are you talking about?

1795
02:19:13.554 --> 02:19:16.842
She's gonna need someone
to grow old with.

1796
02:19:16.932 --> 02:19:19.765
She'll learn to accept
whatever happens. She loves you.

1797
02:19:19.852 --> 02:19:22.594
Honey, she needs a father,
not a playmate.

1798
02:19:22.688 --> 02:19:24.270
(CAROLINE GURGLING)

1799
02:19:26.733 --> 02:19:28.019
- Is it me?
- Of course not.

1800
02:19:28.110 --> 02:19:30.171
- Is my age beginning to bother you?
- Of course not.

1801
02:19:30.195 --> 02:19:34.234
- Is that what you're telling me?
- You can't raise the both of us.

1802
02:19:42.875 --> 02:19:47.790
<i>BENJAMIN: It was your first birthday.
We had a party for you.</i>

1803
02:19:48.547 --> 02:19:50.379
<i>The house was filled with children.</i>

1804
02:19:50.465 --> 02:19:52.422
- How are you?
- Hey, man.

1805
02:19:52.509 --> 02:19:56.173
Before you turn around,
they'll be in high school, dating.

1806
02:20:28.587 --> 02:20:32.581
<i>BENJAMIN: I sold the summer house
on Lake Pontchartrain,</i>

1807
02:20:32.674 --> 02:20:35.416
<i>I sold Button's Buttons,</i>

1808
02:20:35.510 --> 02:20:40.050
<i>I sold my father's sailboat,
put it all into a savings account.</i>

1809
02:20:42.309 --> 02:20:45.518
<i>And so that you and your
mother might have a life,</i>

1810
02:20:46.730 --> 02:20:50.689
<i>I left,
before you could ever remember me.</i>

1811
02:21:13.715 --> 02:21:15.205
(DOOR OPENING)

1812
02:21:40.367 --> 02:21:42.574
"I left with just the
clothes on my back."

1813
02:21:43.912 --> 02:21:48.577
I don't want to read this now.
Can you just tell me where he went?

1814
02:21:50.043 --> 02:21:52.284
I don't really know.

1815
02:22:03.557 --> 02:22:08.518
It's for me. 1970. I was two.
"Happy Birthday.

1816
02:22:11.273 --> 02:22:14.140
"I wish I could have
kissed you good night."

1817
02:22:19.239 --> 02:22:20.980
They're all for me.

1818
02:22:21.992 --> 02:22:26.987
Five. "I wish I could have taken
you to your first day of school."

1819
02:22:31.501 --> 02:22:37.372
Six. "I wish I could have been
there to teach you to play piano."

1820
02:22:40.802 --> 02:22:43.760
1981, 13.

1821
02:22:43.847 --> 02:22:47.181
"I wish I could have told
you not to chase some boy.

1822
02:22:48.477 --> 02:22:52.141
"I wish I could have held you
when you had a broken heart.

1823
02:22:53.648 --> 02:22:59.439
"I wish I could have been your father.
Nothing I ever did will replace that."

1824
02:23:06.912 --> 02:23:09.449
I guess he went to India.

1825
02:23:09.539 --> 02:23:11.997
"For what it's worth,
it's never too late,

1826
02:23:12.084 --> 02:23:15.004
- "or, in my case, too early..."
<i>- BENJAMIN: ...or, in my case, too early,</i>

1827
02:23:15.170 --> 02:23:17.161
<i>to be whoever you want to be.</i>

1828
02:23:21.176 --> 02:23:23.884
<i>There's no time limit.
Start whenever you want.</i>

1829
02:23:26.765 --> 02:23:31.259
<i>You can change or stay the same.
There are no rules to this thing.</i>

1830
02:23:33.814 --> 02:23:37.307
<i>We can make the
best or the worst of it.</i>

1831
02:23:37.400 --> 02:23:39.732
<i>And I hope you make the best of it.</i>

1832
02:23:42.823 --> 02:23:45.531
<i>I hope you see things
that startle you.</i>

1833
02:23:47.702 --> 02:23:51.195
<i>I hope you feel things
you never felt before.</i>

1834
02:23:53.667 --> 02:23:57.205
<i>I hope you meet people
with a different point of view.</i>

1835
02:23:58.338 --> 02:24:01.046
<i>I hope you live a
life you're proud of.</i>

1836
02:24:04.052 --> 02:24:09.092
<i>And if you find that you're not,
I hope you have the strength</i>

1837
02:24:09.182 --> 02:24:12.391
<i>- to start all over again.
- "...start all</i> over <i>again."</i>

1838
02:24:13.937 --> 02:24:17.680
He had been gone a long time.

1839
02:24:19.442 --> 02:24:21.558
I'll see you next Thursday.

1840
02:24:24.531 --> 02:24:27.899
- Good night, Miss Daisy.
- Oh, good night, sweetheart.

1841
02:24:45.760 --> 02:24:47.751
I'm sorry, we're closing.

1842
02:24:50.682 --> 02:24:52.264
Can I help you?

1843
02:24:53.810 --> 02:24:56.268
Are you here to pick somebody up?

1844
02:25:06.615 --> 02:25:08.481
Why did you come back?

1845
02:25:10.076 --> 02:25:11.362
CAROLINE: Mom?

1846
02:25:12.412 --> 02:25:13.493
Mom?

1847
02:25:14.706 --> 02:25:16.242
You ready yet?

1848
02:25:19.211 --> 02:25:20.326
Mom, what's wrong?

1849
02:25:20.420 --> 02:25:24.004
I was just hearing a very sad
story about a mutual friend

1850
02:25:24.090 --> 02:25:26.798
who I hadn't seen for a very long time.

1851
02:25:28.053 --> 02:25:30.795
Caroline, this is Benjamin.

1852
02:25:30.889 --> 02:25:33.631
You knew him when
you were just a baby.

1853
02:25:36.061 --> 02:25:37.301
- Hi.
- Hi.

1854
02:25:39.231 --> 02:25:41.142
Hey.

1855
02:25:43.109 --> 02:25:47.945
- Oh, I'm sorry, I thought you were done.
- Oh, this is a friend of my family's.

1856
02:25:48.031 --> 02:25:52.992
Benjamin Button,
this is my husband, Robert.

1857
02:25:53.078 --> 02:25:55.490
- How do you do?
- A pleasure.

1858
02:26:03.630 --> 02:26:06.622
Well, it was very nice to meet you.

1859
02:26:06.716 --> 02:26:08.548
- We'll be in the car, darling.
- All right.

1860
02:26:08.635 --> 02:26:09.796
Bye.

1861
02:26:10.512 --> 02:26:12.298
I'm just looking up.

1862
02:26:17.018 --> 02:26:18.133
Wow.

1863
02:26:20.647 --> 02:26:23.514
She's beautiful. Like her mother.

1864
02:26:25.110 --> 02:26:27.602
- Does she dance?
- Not very well.

1865
02:26:27.696 --> 02:26:29.607
I guess that'd be
from my side of things.

1866
02:26:29.698 --> 02:26:31.689
She's a dear, sweet girl.

1867
02:26:32.867 --> 02:26:37.236
She seems a little lost.
But then, who isn't at 12?

1868
02:26:37.414 --> 02:26:41.703
A lot of her reminds me of you.

1869
02:26:42.544 --> 02:26:46.538
My husband, he's a widower, or was...
Was a widower.

1870
02:26:46.881 --> 02:26:50.840
He's an incredibly kind, just bright,
adventurous man.

1871
02:26:53.972 --> 02:26:56.714
- He's been a terrific father.
- Good.

1872
02:27:01.396 --> 02:27:05.310
- You are so much younger.
- Only on the outside.

1873
02:27:07.402 --> 02:27:08.938
You were right.

1874
02:27:10.697 --> 02:27:14.065
I couldn't have been
raising both of you.

1875
02:27:14.159 --> 02:27:15.945
I'm not that strong.

1876
02:27:20.123 --> 02:27:22.205
So, where are you staying?

1877
02:27:24.836 --> 02:27:25.836
What are you gonna do?

1878
02:27:25.920 --> 02:27:29.754
I'm staying at the Pontchartrain
Hotel on the Avenue.

1879
02:27:29.841 --> 02:27:33.379
I don't know what I'm gonna do.

1880
02:27:33.470 --> 02:27:34.676
But...

1881
02:27:35.263 --> 02:27:36.753
(HORN HONKING)

1882
02:27:41.144 --> 02:27:42.805
They're waiting.

1883
02:28:24.938 --> 02:28:28.226
I remember that. That was him?

1884
02:28:29.234 --> 02:28:30.770
<i>(STATIC ON TV)</i>

1885
02:28:30.860 --> 02:28:32.129
NURSE: The hurricane
has changed directions.

1886
02:28:32.153 --> 02:28:33.985
It's going to make
landfall sometime soon.

1887
02:28:34.072 --> 02:28:35.883
- Am I supposed to do something?
- Arrangements are being made

1888
02:28:35.907 --> 02:28:37.218
to move people, but it's up to you.

1889
02:28:37.242 --> 02:28:39.108
No. No, we're... We're staying.

1890
02:28:39.202 --> 02:28:41.864
NURSE: I'll let you know
if anything changes.

1891
02:28:43.873 --> 02:28:48.242
"That night, while I was sitting
and wondering why I came back at all,

1892
02:28:48.336 --> 02:28:50.668
"there was a knock at the door."

1893
02:28:54.300 --> 02:28:55.540
BENJAMIN: Come in.

1894
02:29:09.858 --> 02:29:11.519
Are you all right?

1895
02:29:14.612 --> 02:29:18.731
I'm sorry,
I don't know what I'm doing here.

1896
02:29:27.750 --> 02:29:29.286
Nothing lasts.

1897
02:29:32.714 --> 02:29:35.081
I have never stopped loving you.

1898
02:29:41.055 --> 02:29:43.797
Oh, but, Benjamin,
I'm an old woman now.

1899
02:29:54.402 --> 02:29:56.643
BENJAMIN: Some things
you never forget.

1900
02:30:16.925 --> 02:30:18.006
<i>...so few people even know</i>

1901
02:30:18.092 --> 02:30:19.862
<i>that you were ever in jail
in the first place.</i>

1902
02:30:19.886 --> 02:30:22.093
<i>I'll tell you, I am sick about it, too,</i>

1903
02:30:22.180 --> 02:30:24.763
<i>because, please,
if they're not gonna give you an award</i>

1904
02:30:24.849 --> 02:30:26.931
<i>like Man of the Year,"
at least what they could do</i>

1905
02:30:27.018 --> 02:30:29.680
<i>is stop having you listed
as an ex-convict</i>

1906
02:30:29.771 --> 02:30:32.308
<i>which I think is, again, so unfair.</i>

1907
02:30:45.078 --> 02:30:46.910
Good night, Benjamin.

1908
02:30:48.414 --> 02:30:50.121
Good night, Daisy.

1909
02:30:53.294 --> 02:30:57.538
<i>BENJAMIN: And as I knew I would,
I watched her go.</i>

1910
02:31:00.260 --> 02:31:02.592
That's the last thing he wrote.

1911
02:31:03.721 --> 02:31:08.306
Sometime after your father passed,

1912
02:31:08.393 --> 02:31:11.260
<i>there was a call.</i>

1913
02:31:12.355 --> 02:31:14.221
(PHONE RINGING)

1914
02:31:14.315 --> 02:31:15.476
Hello.

1915
02:31:16.568 --> 02:31:18.104
Yes, speaking.

1916
02:31:21.406 --> 02:31:23.898
I'm sorry, I don't understand.

1917
02:31:33.710 --> 02:31:35.621
It's the corner house.

1918
02:31:38.464 --> 02:31:40.375
(PEOPLE CHATTERING)

1919
02:31:57.775 --> 02:31:59.186
Come on in.

1920
02:32:04.741 --> 02:32:06.778
- I'm Daisy Fuller.
- I'm David Hernandez,

1921
02:32:06.868 --> 02:32:10.611
with the Orleans Parish Department
of Child Welfare Services.

1922
02:32:10.705 --> 02:32:13.367
He was living in a condemned building.

1923
02:32:15.126 --> 02:32:17.458
The police found this with him.

1924
02:32:17.545 --> 02:32:20.503
This address.
It's got your name in it a lot.

1925
02:32:21.674 --> 02:32:24.291
He's in very poor health.
He was taken to the hospital.

1926
02:32:24.385 --> 02:32:28.470
He doesn't seem to know who
or where he is. He's very confused.

1927
02:32:28.556 --> 02:32:32.140
I was telling Mr. Hernandez
that Benjamin is one of us.

1928
02:32:32.226 --> 02:32:36.060
If he needs a place to stay,
it's all right, he can stay here.

1929
02:32:37.065 --> 02:32:40.023
(PIANO PLAYING)

1930
02:33:05.510 --> 02:33:06.796
Benjamin?

1931
02:33:08.012 --> 02:33:09.252
(MUTTERS)

1932
02:33:10.640 --> 02:33:12.472
You play beautifully.

1933
02:33:15.937 --> 02:33:17.803
DAVID: He doesn't seem
to like to be touched.

1934
02:33:17.897 --> 02:33:19.617
He goes in and out
of states of recognition.

1935
02:33:19.649 --> 02:33:21.377
The doctors say,
if they didn't know any better,

1936
02:33:21.401 --> 02:33:23.859
he has the beginnings of dementia.

1937
02:33:25.613 --> 02:33:27.399
Do you remember me?

1938
02:33:30.535 --> 02:33:31.900
I'm Daisy.

1939
02:33:34.455 --> 02:33:35.945
I'm Benjamin.

1940
02:33:41.629 --> 02:33:44.337
It's nice to meet you, Benjamin.

1941
02:33:46.008 --> 02:33:51.424
Would you mind if I sit with you?
I would love to hear you play.

1942
02:33:55.268 --> 02:33:56.804
Do I know you?

1943
02:34:01.733 --> 02:34:03.460
BENJAMIN: I want some breakfast.
<i>DAISY: And every day,</i>

1944
02:34:03.484 --> 02:34:07.443
<i>I would stop by to make sure
that he was comfortable.</i>

1945
02:34:07.530 --> 02:34:10.192
- BENJAMIN: No, I didn't.
- You just finished eating.

1946
02:34:10.283 --> 02:34:12.615
Don't think I don't know
what you're doing!

1947
02:34:12.702 --> 02:34:15.444
You're all fucking liars!

1948
02:34:15.538 --> 02:34:18.496
He doesn't believe
he just had his breakfast.

1949
02:34:19.792 --> 02:34:23.410
Now, why don't we see

1950
02:34:23.504 --> 02:34:26.917
if we can't find something
else for you to do?

1951
02:34:27.049 --> 02:34:30.258
I have a feeling there's a
lot of things I can't remember.

1952
02:34:30.344 --> 02:34:32.255
Well, like what, sugar?

1953
02:34:33.514 --> 02:34:37.508
It's like there's
this whole life I had,

1954
02:34:38.978 --> 02:34:41.390
and I can't remember what it was.

1955
02:34:44.192 --> 02:34:45.523
It's okay.

1956
02:34:47.612 --> 02:34:49.102
It's okay to forget things.

1957
02:34:49.322 --> 02:34:54.908
<i>DAISY: Many times, he would simply
forget who or where he was.</i>

1958
02:34:55.203 --> 02:34:56.910
There he is, he's up there on the roof.

1959
02:34:56.996 --> 02:34:58.703
<i>It wasn't easy.</i>

1960
02:34:58.790 --> 02:35:01.031
- Benjamin!
- I can see everything!

1961
02:35:01.125 --> 02:35:02.911
- I can see the big river!
- That's right,

1962
02:35:03.002 --> 02:35:04.743
you can see everything, sweetheart.

1963
02:35:04.837 --> 02:35:06.828
I can see the graveyard
where Mama's buried,

1964
02:35:06.923 --> 02:35:10.291
- and all those other people.
- I want you to come down!

1965
02:35:10.384 --> 02:35:14.173
- What if I could fly?
- I knew a man who could fly.

1966
02:35:15.139 --> 02:35:18.131
You come down
and I'll tell you all about him.

1967
02:35:21.687 --> 02:35:23.303
Somebody go up there.

1968
02:35:29.904 --> 02:35:32.862
<i>DAISY: He was five when I moved in.</i>

1969
02:35:32.949 --> 02:35:37.443
<i>Nearly the same age I was
when I had met him.</i>

1970
02:35:38.996 --> 02:35:40.782
(ALARM BEEPING)

1971
02:35:43.417 --> 02:35:47.376
"This is the picture
of Old Man Kangaroo

1972
02:35:47.463 --> 02:35:49.921
"at 5:00 in the afternoon

1973
02:35:50.007 --> 02:35:53.500
"when he had got
his beautiful hind legs."

1974
02:35:54.720 --> 02:35:56.006
<i>DAISY: The days passed.</i>

1975
02:35:56.097 --> 02:36:00.386
<i>And I watched as he forgot how to walk</i>

1976
02:36:05.606 --> 02:36:08.064
<i>- and how to talk.</i>
- What's my name?

1977
02:36:08.484 --> 02:36:09.849
I'm Daisy.

1978
02:36:10.987 --> 02:36:12.773
Can you say "Daisy"?

1979
02:36:14.323 --> 02:36:19.614
<i>In 2002, they put up a new
clock in that train station.</i>

1980
02:36:26.460 --> 02:36:30.249
<i>And in the spring of 2003,</i>

1981
02:36:34.594 --> 02:36:36.301
<i>he looked at me</i>

1982
02:36:38.764 --> 02:36:43.850
<i>and I knew that he knew who I was.</i>

1983
02:36:47.356 --> 02:36:53.193
<i>And then he closed his eyes
as if to go to sleep.</i>

1984
02:37:25.728 --> 02:37:29.938
- I wish I'd known him.
- Now you do.

1985
02:37:30.024 --> 02:37:31.355
(ALARM BLARING)

1986
02:37:32.193 --> 02:37:34.309
(PEOPLE CLAMORING)

1987
02:37:34.403 --> 02:37:38.192
Mom, I think I should go
see what's going on.

1988
02:37:39.033 --> 02:37:41.821
(LOUD RUMBLING)

1989
02:37:45.206 --> 02:37:47.288
Good night, Benjamin.

1990
02:38:09.647 --> 02:38:12.084
<i>MAN ON TV: We're expecting
flash flooding after the levee break.</i>

1991
02:38:12.108 --> 02:38:14.395
<i>It occurred in the Ninth Ward.</i>

1992
02:38:17.405 --> 02:38:20.238
<i>BENJAMIN: Some people
are born to sit by a river.</i>

1993
02:38:21.742 --> 02:38:23.733
<i>Some get struck by lightning.</i>

1994
02:38:25.579 --> 02:38:27.741
<i>Some have an ear for music.</i>

1995
02:38:29.291 --> 02:38:30.952
<i>Some are artists.</i>

1996
02:38:32.253 --> 02:38:33.618
<i>Some swim.</i>

1997
02:38:35.047 --> 02:38:36.708
<i>Some know buttons.</i>

1998
02:38:38.467 --> 02:38:39.878
<i>Some know Shakespeare.</i>

1999
02:38:41.012 --> 02:38:42.798
<i>Some are mothers.</i>

2000
02:38:44.765 --> 02:38:47.803
<i>And some people dance.</i>

2001
02:39:07.204 --> 02:39:11.539
(TICKING)

